<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Brutality     02-28 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Brutality,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commander Warns Officers Against `Rabble' Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior commander ordered his officers Sunday
to view film footage of troops brutally beating Arab prisoners and
said the Israeli army must not become ``a rabble army.''
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, head of the Central Command that is in
charge of the occupied West Bank of the Jordan River, gathered all
officers over the rank of platoon commander Sunday and showed them
the footage shot by CBS News in the West Bank town of Nablus,
Israel radio reported.
   ``I'm against those who think we can sweep internal problems
under the carpet just because they're not pretty,'' Mitzna said
earlier on Israel radio. ``We have to make sure we don't become a
rabble army.''
   The film, which showed four soldiers in Nablus kicking and
beating two Palestinians last Thursday, shocked many Israelis who
believed violence by soldiers during three months of Palestinian
demonstrations had receded after new army orders last week limited
the use of force.
   Some members of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud
Bloc defended the soldiers.
   ``I'm against the lynch atmosphere,'' said Likud legislator
Pinchas Goldstein. ``There was no need to arrest the soldiers.''
   Transport Minister Chaim Korfu, also of Likud, told the Cabinet
Sunday the press should be barred from the occupied lands for three
months.
   ``We are in a confrontation,'' Korfu later told Israel army
radio. ``We must take these minimal measures when we know for
certain (the media) is responsible for some of the violence.''
   According to U.N. figures, 74 Arabs have been killed by the
Israelis during the violent in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip since Dec. 10. Hundreds have been wounded and there have been
many cases of soldiers severely beating Palestinians.
   The CBS film showed four soldiers, members of a tank unit,
kicking the Palestinians whose hands were tied behind their backs
and smashing them on the legs and arms with fist-sized rocks.
   The four were arrested and their deputy unit commander, a
captain, was suspended. It was announced Saturday that the four
soldiers would be tried by a military court. Mitzna ordered the
release of the two Arabs.
   Amalia Harpaz, the mother of one of the four soldiers filmed by
CBS, said her son Saguy had changed since he began serving in the
occupied territories 10 weeks ago.
   ``I educated my son to go the army, take responsibility and
defend the country,'' she told Israel radio. ``What has happened is
that he has turned into a beater of women and children.''
   She is a resident of Kibbutz Gesher, a communal settlement.
   Israel radio said several lawyers have offered to represent the
soldiers without charge. It reported the lawyers said if anyone was
responsible for a crime, it is Israel's leaders.
</TEXT>
