<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0828 02-28 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0828,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunken Barge Raised, Minor Oil Spill Detected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with oil pumping under way,
increased estimate on surface oil spill, updated figure on amount
of this spill cleaned up. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Western
Washington ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG ESSER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANACORTES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A salvage crew raised a sunken oil barge
Sunday from the murky depths of Guemes Channel, one month after it
sank and spilled some 70,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil into
Washington's inland waters.
   With the inverted barge held at the surface by thick cables
strung from two giant cranes, crews began pumping the more than
300,000 gallons of oil that remained in the vessel into a second
barge. Officials said they wanted to get the stricken barge
floating on its own before they attempted to slowly roll it right
side up.
   A helicopter hovered overhead to track the movement of an oil
sheen that appeared as the barge was raised. The sheen was caused
by 500 to 1,000 gallons of lighter oil that was detected after the
barge broke the surface about 7 a.m., said Mark Stewart of the
state Division of Emergency Management.
   The barge initially held about 22,000 gallons of light oil in
addition to the heavy oil.
   Stewart said surface skimmer boats had cleaned up about 160
gallons, while absorbent pads collected an additional, undetermined
amount.
   The oil sheen moved about two miles south. Coast Guard Lt. Eldo
DeLong said the sheen reached some kelp beds near Burrows Bay, but
did not touch any beaches.
   State Department of Ecology workers said three seabirds were
contaminated, but they did not appear badly injured and were not
captured for cleaning.
   Marine biologists and state environmental experts were assessing
the damage from the bunker oil spill, which had been difficult to
determine because the heavier-than-water oil had sunk.
   But Ats Kiuchi, a DOE spokesman, said it appeared the fragile,
inner coastal environment had avoided a disaster that, if the barge
had spilled its entire cargo, would have been the worst oil spill
in the state's history.
   Western Washington University's Shannon Point Marine Laboratory
has found some oil in sea cucumbers, said Paul Cassidy, the lab's
director of operations.
   The U.S. Coast Guard tug ``Spike'' used absorbent pads to clean
up some oil after the barge was raised while a second boat was
positioned near Shannon Point, 100 yards away, to prevent any oil
from reaching shore.
   The 176-foot-long barge, operated by Olympic Tug and Barge of
Seattle, sank Jan. 31 in about 130 feet of water four miles west of
Anacortes and about 100 yards off Shannon Point.
   The barge had been loaded at an oil refinery at Anacortes and
was being towed by a tug to Seattle when it began listing and
capsized.
   The cause of the sinking remained undetermined.
   Coast Guard Lt. Eldo DeLong said the barge will be taken to the
Anacortes city dock where a boom would be put around it and any
remaining holes would be patched. Eventually it will be taken to
Seattle, he said.
</TEXT>
