<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Iran     02-28 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iran,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: United States Has Sent Envoy To Iran For Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A London newspaper said Sunday that the United
States has sent a secret envoy to Iran to discuss re-establishing
diplomatic links.
   The Observer, in an unattributed story, did not identify the
official but said he is apparently a close friend of President
Reagan and went to Tehran two weeks ago. It said the envoy was
traveling under the name of Clark.
   The Observer said the envoy met middle-ranking Iranian
officials, who asked for assurances that any arms embargo against
them as proposed by the United Nations should be delayed until
early this summer.
   The United States is seeking a U.N. ban on arms sales because
Iran has not accepted a cease-fire agreement in its eight-year war
with Iraq.
   There have been no diplomatic relations since the U.S. embassy
in Tehran was stormed Nov. 4, 1979, and held for 444 days with
diplomats and others kept hostage inside.
</TEXT>
