<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MilitaryCourts     02-28 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military Courts,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel's Military Court System Under Hail Of Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOD, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Abu Leban, accused of hurling a
firebomb at Israeli soldiers, saw his lawyer for the first time
five minutes before he appeared in military court.
   The 19-year-old signed a confession written in Hebrew, a
language he does not know, and said interrogators abused him.
   As authorities round up growing numbers of Arab suspects in an
effort to quell nearly three months of unrest, Israel's methods of
detaining and trying Palestinians has drawn a hail of criticism.
   ``I feel totally helpless in this sham of a system,'' said Abu
Leban's attorney, Jonathan Kuttab, a Palestinian who graduated from
the University of Virginia law school in Charlottesville.
   ``In 98 percent of the cases, lawyers cannot see Palestinian
clients until after they `confess,' and judges will accept the
`confession' at face value, no matter what you say,'' Kuttab told
The Associated Press.
   Abu Leban, shackled and dressed in a blue-jeans jacket, flashed
a V-for-victory sign as he entered the tiny courtroom in a closed
army base. He waved to his father, whom he was seeing for the first
time since his arrest.
   Abu Leban had been held incommunicado for 18 days, until he
signed a four-page confession. He said he signed only after
interrogators beat him, deprived him of sleep and forced him to
squat in a corner for hours.
   Kuttab said it was unlikely his client's contentions would be
accepted in court. Allegations of unfairness in the military court
system prompted the attorneys' association in the Gaza Strip to
decide to boycott all military court proceedings.
   But Israeli officials argue the system is fair.
   ``There are some exceptions. But a defendant who feels he was
mistreated during interrogation can raise the issue in court, where
due process of law is ensured,'' army prosecutor Amos Giora, a
native of Ann Arbor, Mich., said in an interview.
   Giora and other Israelis argue the only obvious shortcoming in
the military court system was redressed by Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin earlier this month when he announced that Israel, after 20
years of occupation, would establish army appeal courts.
   Kuttab said figures assembled by Palestinian lawyers show the
total number of Arab detainees, normally about 3,000 at any one
time, has doubled and the army has set up four new prisons with
tent barracks in the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
   According to the army, 1,927 Palestinians were arrested and 93
placed in jail for six months without trial under emergency
regulations from Dec. 8 to Feb. 9. The Arab-owned Palestine Press
Service puts the number of Arabs jailed without trial at 147.
   The process from arrest to trial in the military court system is
well documented. A Palestinian suspected of participating in
anti-Israeli activities is usually detained in the middle of the
night because soldiers fear their presence in Arab towns or refugee
camps during the day might spark protests.
   The detainee is handcuffed, often blindfolded, and taken to a
military prison. No arrest warrant is ever shown and family members
are not told where the suspect is being taken.
   It often takes a lawyer several weeks to track down his new
client, who can be held incommunicado for up to six months. A judge
is required to order a detention extension after the first 18 days.
   ``During the period of interrogation, the detainee is routinely
subjected to beatings, forced to spend long hours in uncomfortable
positions, threatened and submitted to other psychological
measures,'' Kuttab said.
   ``Usually before the first 18-day period is up, the defendant
breaks down and confesses to a variety of illegal activities,''
Kuttab said. ``Only after this is he permitted to see an attorney,
and only then is the attorney told what charges his client faces.''
   Abu Leban entered court with five other Arab defendants, four of
whom had no attorney present. Kuttab was able to see his client and
the charge sheet against him only minutes before the court session
began.
   Kuttab argued in court that Abu Leban signed the confession only
after being abused. He asked for, and was granted, a separate
hearing about the admissiblity of the evidence.
   Kuttab said he did not intend actually to present a case on
whether the evidence should be admitted, but only to use the extra
time to try to plea bargain a shorter sentence.
   ``If I protest, his interrogator will deny it and he will just
end up getting a tougher sentence,'' Kuttab said.
   ``What hurts most about the process is the pretense of
propriety,'' he said. ``With a judge and a prosecutor and a defense
attorney, it looks all right from the outside. But in fact, on a
certain level, I feel I am a collaborator in the evil system.''
   ``At least I brought him some cigarettes,'' Kuttab said of Abu
Leban, shaking his head as he left court. ``I've turned into a
social worker more than a lawyer in this system.''
</TEXT>
