<HEAD>Suspect Rearrested In Assault Of Miss USA Co-Host</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with man freed on bond again,
real name determined, picking up 6th graf pvs, `I'm shocked...'.
SUBS penultimate graf, `If convicted...', to give suspect's real
name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of attempting to sexually
assault actress Tracy Scoggins, a co-host of the Miss USA pageant
here, was rearrested Saturday after a judge's decision to set him
free on $100 bond sparked protests.
   He later was freed again after posting a much higher bond.
   The man, Pedro Concepcion Padilla, 35, of El Paso, was initially
arrested Thursday night after the assault in a hotel elevator. He
was released early Friday on $100 bond set by associate municipal
magistrate Rodolfo Romero. But the low bond infuriated State
District Judge Brunson Moore, as well as Miss Scoggins, and Moore
ordered him arrested again.
   Padilla turned himself in at 9:35 a.m. Saturday and jailed again
on $100,000 bond. He posted the required 15 percent of that amount
later in the day and was freed after spending about five hours in
custody.
   Officials said the man originally gave authorities a false name,
Antonio Garcia.
   He was re-arrested through the help of his attorney, according
to sheriff's Capt. Paco Aguirre.
   ``I'm shocked and I'm outraged,'' Miss Scoggins said Friday
after the suspect's release. ``What this says to me is that a man
like this can save himself a whole expensive night of dinner and
dancing and just pay $100 to assault the woman of his choice.
That's a pretty good deal.''
   Miss Scoggins, who starred in the ABC television series ``The
Colbys,'' suffered minor bruises during the attack. Security guards
and other guests who heard her screams came to her aid and subdued
the attacker, she said.
   If convicted, Padilla could be sentenced to up to 10 years in
prison and fined up to $5,000.
   Miss Scoggins, who lives in Malibu, Calif., is in El Paso to be
co-host of the Miss USA pageant, which will be broadcast live
Tuesday nationwide.
</TEXT>
