<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0669 02-28 1116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0669,1,050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Delvalle Decided on His Own To Go Into Hiding</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new 3rd graf and INSERTS 9 grafs after 5th graf pvs
bgng, `President Reagan' to UPDATE with OAS debate, playing of tape
of Mrs. Delvalle; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs bgng, `Chewning said
questions'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan administration officials said Saturday
that Eric Arturo Delvalle, recognized by the United States as
Panama's president, decided on his own to go into hiding, but that
he remained in telephone contact with U.S. diplomats in Panama City.
   Delvalle is ``safe and in high spirits'' after escaping arrest,
and the struggle against the country's military leader will
continue, Delvalle's envoy to Washington said.
   The permanent council of the Organization of American States,
after a lengthy and at times heated debate Saturday night on the
situation in Panama, took no position on the turmoil there.
   Reagan administration officials denied participating in
Delvalle's escape, though they said the U.S. ambassador to Panama,
Arthur H. Davis, was in contact with Delvalle by telephone.
   They said they were not sure what Delvalle's next move would be.
   President Reagan, who usually spends weekends at Camp David,
Md., was at the White House receiving reports on the fast-moving
situation.
   The 30-member OAS council sidestepped a decision on whether to
seat as Panama's ambassador to the organization Robert Leyton, the
current envoy who is loyal to Panamanian military chief Manuel
Antonio Noriega, or Larence Chewning Fabrega, Delvalle's delegate.
There had been indications from officials of the American
delegation that the council would seat neither man, chosing instead
to recognize Soraya Cano, a Panamanian career diplomat who is a
member of the Panamanian delegation to the OAS.
   The start of the formal council debate had been delayed for five
hours while the envoys wrangled in private over the question of
whom to credential as Panama's representative.
   But when the debate commenced, shortly after 9 p.m. EST, no
resolutions were offered dealing with that sticky question.
Instead, Leyton was admitted to take part in the debate, at least
for the time being, and he launched into a tirade against the
United States, accusing it of trying to destabilize his government.
   ``I wish to somehow resolve the crisis in the government of
Panama,'' Leyton said. ``But this is not the forum.''
   Leyton steadfastly denied U.S. charges that Noriega has been
involved in drug trafficking, although the former Panamanian
ambassador to the United States, Gabriel Lewis, told the council,
``We are suffering a new phenomenon _ narco-militarism. This
narcotic militarism knows no frontier.''
   Richard T. McCormack, the U.S. ambassador to the OAS, said the
United States could not accept the decision by the Panamanian
National Assembly in which Delvalle was deposed ``in a 10-minute
rump session.''
   In a riveting moment, Lewis had OAS technicians play an
audio-cassette in which he had tape-recorded the telephone
conversation with Delvalle's wife, Mariela, as Panamanian military
personnel surrounded her house after her husband had fled.
   Mrs. Delvalle, in a trembling voice, described how she had told
the officers ``My husband isn't here, nor are you going to find
him.''
   A member of the U.S. mission, declining to be identified
publicly, indicated that a part of the problem for the OAS
ambassadors in deciding which Panamanian representative to
credential was that they had doubts about what stance they should
take. ``They're afraid of doing something which might prejudice the
position their government has taken'' on Noriega, the official said.
   Chewning said questions also had been raised about whether El
Salvador's ambassador, Ernesto Rivas Gallont, had the right to
request the special session, with some ambassadors who support
Noriega opposing it.
   Chewning said those who oppose having the issue debated in the
OAS ``simply don't want the rest of the world to know what's going
on in Panama.''
   He said the ambassadors had not allowed him or Leyton to address
the gathering.
   Jose B. Sosa, the Panamanian ambassador accredited to the U.S.
government, said in an interview on Cable News Network's
``Newsmaker Saturday'' that he was in touch with Delvalle
supporters in Panama City and ``we understand he is physically all
right, he's safe and in high spirits,''
   ``The struggle that President Delvalle is leading now is a
struggle to get the country back to civilian rule and get the
country into democratic process and that's what the Panamanian
people want,'' Sosa said. ``That's why we feel we are going to
carry the struggle, carry this fight.''
   ``The Panamanian people are going to rally behind the
constitutional president, he is going to win this out,'' Sosa said.
   U.S. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
United States had nothing to do with Delvalle's decision to leave
his house to avoid arrest, but that the Panamanian had been in
touch with Davis by telephone.
   They denied initially that the United States knew Delvalle's
whereabouts, but later in the day, when asked if U.S. officials
knew where Delvalle had gone, they said, ``he is at an undisclosed
location.''
   According to the U.S. officials' account, soldiers came to
Delvalle's house at 8 a.m. and were met at the door by Delvalle's
wife. While the soldiers were telling her they wanted to take
Delvalle, the president escaped out a back door, the officials said.
   ``It was his own decision, we did not do this,'' said one
official, when asked if the United States had participated in
Delvalle's escape.
   Several of Delvalle's family members, including several children
and grandchildren, stayed overnight at the U.S. Embassy in Panama
City, the officials said.
   The officials reaffirmed a U.S. decision to continue recognizing
Delvalle as Panama's president, despite his replacement by a
cabinet minister loyal to Noriega.
   Delvalle's flight posed a dilemma for U.S. policy-makers because
his departure for the United States or another country would remove
a key anti-Noriega symbol around which opposition to military rule
could gather.
   Administration officials said on Saturday they hoped to marshal
international support behind Delvalle's presidency, notably among
Central American nations.
   High-level meetings continued at the State Department, where
officials described the situation in Panama City as calm.
   They said the 10,000 American troops in Panama _ assigned to
protection of the Panama Canal _ were continuing to keep a low
profile.
   The United States policy toward Noriega has grown increasingly
hostile in recent months and the sentiment intensified after Feb.
5, when two federal grand juries returned indictments portraying
him as a key conspirator in an international drug trafficking
operation.
   Delvalle had been viewed by the administration as little more
than a front man for Noriega, but that all changed Thursday evening
when he broke with the military chieftain.
</TEXT>
