<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TransplantDeath     02-28 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplant Death,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amy Hardin, 5, Dies Five Years After Liver Transplant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAHOKIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amy Lynn Hardin, the infant who won the
hearts of supporters from Southern Illinois to the White House when
she became the youngest liver transplant recipient five years ago,
died Saturday at her home here.
   She was 5 years old. The transplanted liver Amy received on May
10, 1983, had begun to fail around Thanksgiving, said her mother,
Robin Hardin.
   On Dec. 11, the family took Amy to the University of Minnesota
Hospital in Minneapolis, where the transplant had been performed.
But the girl returned home Jan. 16 after doctors said her chances
for recovery were not good.
   ``She couldn't stand it anymore,'' Mrs. Hardin said. ``We made a
promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. We brought
her home and the family took turns being with her.''
   ``She's at peace now,'' Mrs. Hardin said.
   People throughout the region rallied in late 1982 and early 1983
to raise more than $260,000 through a variety of fund-raisers to
pay for what then was considered an experimental transplant
operation.
   The rock group Kiss performed a benefit concert for Amy in 1983
at Kiel Auditorium in St. Louis. That same year, Amy received a
letter of support from President Reagan.
   ``If it wasn't for the community getting together, we wouldn't
have had five years,'' Mrs. Hardin said. ``She was the joy of our
life. She was very strong. She fought all the way to the end.''
   Amy was 11 months old at the time of the transplant. At that
time, she was believed to be the world's youngest liver transplant
patient. That record since has been broken, said Mary Stanik, media
relations director for University of Minnesota Hospital.
   Ms. Stanik said the survival rate of most liver transplant
patients improves with time. ``Usually, but not always, doctors
like to say that you are over the hump after five years, but one
can never say never. There are just too many complications,'' she
said.
   Amy died nearly four years and 10 months after her transplant.
She would have turned 6 years old June 1.
   Besides her parents, Amy is survived by two brothers. Funeral
services were set for Monday.
</TEXT>
