<1ST_LINE>b i AM-Panama 6thLd-Writethru a0703 02-28 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0703,0867</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ousted President Flees House; Ordered Out of Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to RESTORE attribution. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs, ```I'm going ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Arturo Delvalle fled his house
hours after government agents warned him to leave the country, a
relative said. The deposed president later vowed from hiding
Saturday to fight any attempt to expel him.
   Delvalle slipped away on foot ``to protect himself'' _ to avoid
arrest and deportation by military strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the ousted president's brother-in-law, Raul Diaz, told
reporters.
   ``I'm going to stay here and I'm going to stick it out. I'm
going to fight it all the way,'' Delvalle later told ABC News by
telephone. ``I want you to let the world to know that I'm in
Panama, that you spoke to me, that I'm not leaving anywhere.''
   He refused to disclose his whereabouts.
   The U.S. State Department also said Delvalle remained in Panama
and had been in contact with U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis.
   ABC News said it had been contacted by the ousted president, and
quoted the State Department as saying Delvalle was not at a U.S.
installation. Panama's canal zone is headquarters to the
10,000-troop U.S. Southern Command, which runs U.S. military
operations in Latin America.
   The National Assembly, with opposition lawmakers boycotting,
ousted Delvalle Friday, a day after he tried to fire Noriega as
Defense Forces chief.
   Noriega, who controls the 15,000-strong military and police and
is the power behind the civilian government, is under U.S.
indictment on drug trafficking charges and claims the United States
was behind the attempt to fire him.
   Diaz said security agents under Noriega's command had on Friday
told Delvalle to leave Panama. Delvalle refused to accept his
ouster. The United States also continued to recognize him.
   Ana Raquel Delvalle, sister of the ousted president, said family
members had visited him and found, ``He is well, calm, in a secure
place and continues carrying out his functions as president of
Panama.''
   Deposed Vice President Roderick Esquivel and his family also
dropped out of sight Saturday. Top officials of his Liberal Party
said they had talked to him by telephone, but said he would not
reveal his whereabouts out of concern for his safety.
   Esquivel was dismissed early Friday along with Delvalle.
   Meanwhile, a national strike called by the main opposition group
got off to a slow start Saturday.
   Soldiers came to Delvalle's house at 8 a.m. and were met at the
door by Delvalle's wife, Mariela. While the soldiers were telling
her they wanted to take Delvalle, the president escaped out a back
door, according to U.S. officials in Washington.
   The State Department sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Delvalle had been in telephone contact with Davis
and that members of his family were at the U.S. Embassy.
   Diplomats said they expected Noriega's government would file
criminal charges against the deposed president.
   Bereft of power, Delvalle told reporters Friday night: ``I don't
have a seat of government, nor military support, but I do have 2
million Panamanians who are tired and bored of living under a
regime that one man has governed capriciously, and because of that
I call for national resistance to paralyze the entire country
starting Monday.''
   He also urged a worldwide trade embargo against Panama.
   The opposition National Civic Crusade called an immediate
general strike. The coalition of 200 groups has been calling since
last June for the ouster of Noriega, who has run the country since
1983.
   Aurelio Barria, president of the Panamanian Chamber of Commerce
and Industry, said the Crusade hoped to ``totally paralyze'' the
nation by early next week.
   Still, most shops and other businesses were open Saturday
morning, although they traditionally close their doors at noon for
the remainder of the weekend.
   Police threw up barricades Friday and blocked the short street
in Panama City where Delvalle's modest but modern home is located,
refusing to allow Davis and Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., to visit
Delvalle.
   Other policemen could be seen in the front yard of the small
house.
   At noon Saturday, the barricades where withdrawn. Diaz then came
out and spoke to reporters.
   Diaz said a police officer called at the Delvalle home Saturday
morning and told family members the former president should leave
Panama.
   Later, he said security agents had also contacted Delvalle
Friday, warning him to leave the country.
   The United States has called for Noriega's removal since he was
indicted in Florida on Feb. 5 on drug trafficking charges. The
indictment says Noriega allegedly let Colombian narcotics
traffickers use Panama as a base for smuggling cocaine and
marijuana into the United States, receiving kickbacks from drug
profits.
   Noriega has blamed protests that began last summer and the
indictment on efforts by U.S. conservatives to prevent transfer of
the Panama Canal to this country by the end of 1999.
   American military personnel in Panama were on alert and
civilians were told to keep a low profile.
</TEXT>
