<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DonorBabies     02-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Donor Babies,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life Support Pulled From Texas Infant With Almost No Brain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas infant born with almost no
brain was taken off life-support equipment that was intended to
help preserve her tiny heart and other organs for transplantation,
a doctor said Saturday.
   ``Baby Evelyn continues to breathe on her own, but shows signs
of gradual deterioration,'' Dr. Joyce Peabody, chief of neonatology
at Loma Linda University Medical Center, said in a statement late
Saturday.
   Evelyn Keys was born with a fatal genetic birth defect known as
anencephaly, in which much of the upper brain and skull are
missing. Loma Linda has developed the nation's first guidelines
using such infants as organ donors.
   However, little Evelyn never met the hospital's criteria for
brain-death since she was born seven days ago, and machine-assisted
breathing was stopped Saturday, with her parents' consent, Peabody
said.
   Although three newborns needing healthy livers had been
identified during the week, the likelihood of a vital organ
transplant dropped to nil, hospital spokesman Anita Rockwell said.
   Baby Evelyn will be allowed to die naturally, she said.
   ``It is highly unlikely that she will be able to donate organs
such as liver and heart, because without continuation of assisted
breathing, oxygen deprivation of these organs will occur prior to
her death,'' Ms. Rockwell said.
   Details about the potential liver recipients weren't disclosed,
but Ms. Rockwell said they weren't at Loma Linda.
   Evelyn was born Feb. 20 in San Antonio, Texas, to Judy Keys, 22,
and Airman Todd Keys, 21, stationed at Lackland Air Force Base. The
infant was flown to Loma Linda that same day to be used in the
donor program.
   Anencephalic babies usually die within days after birth.
   Loma Linda, a pioneer in infant heart transplants, has sought to
establish a practice of sustaining anencephalic babies so vital
organs can be used after brain death is certified by two
independent physicians. Under the hospital's rules, however, no
baby is kept on life-support longer than a week, whether brain
death has occurred during that time or not.
   Loma Linda doctors anticipate that Baby Evelyn's heart valves,
and perhaps corneas will be donated after her heart stops, Ms.
Rockwell said.
   The same day Evelyn was born, another anencephalic baby,
identified only as Baby John, died at Loma Linda after efforts find
a suitable liver or heart recipient were unsuccessful. He had been
declared brain dead two days earlier. In his case, doctors were
able to use a heart valve after he died.
</TEXT>
