<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sikhs     02-28 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sikhs,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wanted Sikh Militant Killed In Gunfight With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sikh extremist wanted in the 1986
murder of former army chief Arun S. Vaidya was killed Saturday in a
gunbattle with police, the United News of India reported.
   The news agency quoted Punjab state police chief J. F. Ribeiro
as saying Surindra Singh was killed after he was challenged by a
police patrol in Chandigarh, the state capital.
   One of the militant's accomplices, identified as Harjinder
Singh, was also killed while another was injured, Ribeiro said.
   Surindra Singh is one of the more than 20 militants believed to
be involved in the Aug. 10, 1986 assassination of Vaidya in Pune,
in western India. Two others, Ranjit Singh Gill and Sukhminder
Singh, were arrested in New Jersey last year and are facing
extradition proceedings.
   Another eight suspects have been arrested in India.
   Vaidya was the army chief when soldiers stormed the Golden
Temple in the Sikh holy city of Amritsar in 1984 to dislodge Sikh
extremists who were using it as a base. Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards later in the
year.
   Meanwhile, police in Amritsar, 130 miles northwest of
Chandigarh, blamed Sikh extremists for the killing of seven members
of a Sikh family in a nearby village.
   Amritsar District police chief Izhar Alam said the family was
slain Friday night by six Sikhs armed with automatic rifles. The
killings occurred in Talwandi Chamchuk village, 25 miles west of
Amritsar.
   UNI quoted unnamed police sources as saying the family
apparently refused to pay extortion money to the Khalistan
Liberation Force, one of several Sikh militant groups active in
Punjab.
   In other militant-related violence in the state, a Hindu
policeman was killed by Sikh radicals early Saturday near the town
of Ludhiana in central Punjab, police said.
   The killings raised to at least 304 the numkber of people killed
this year in attacks blamed on Sikh militants. Nearly two-thirds of
the victims have been Sikhs.
   Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1983 for a
separate state in Punjab, which they propose to call Khalistan.
   Last year, more than 1,000 people were killed in Punjab by the
militants.
   Sikhs, whose religion is an offshoot of Hinduism, claim they are
discriminated against by India's Hindu majority. Sikhs comprise
about 2 percent of India's 800 million population but are a
majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
