<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel-Violence,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arabs Shot To Death, Cabinet Debates Barring Media From
Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABUD, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab reports said Israeli
soldiers opened fire to quell riots sparked by Jewish settlers who
tried to enter a West Bank village at night. The army on Sunday
confirmed two Arabs were shot to death.
   Meanwhile, Israel's navy sank a boat carrying guerrillas who
were en route from Lebanon to launch an attack on Israel. Lebanese
police said two Palestinian fighters were killed in the incident
Saturday night and three swam to shore.
   Also, three Arab guerrillas were killed in southern Lebanon
early Sunday after they stormed an outpost of pro-Israeli Lebanese
militiamen in Beit Yaoun near Israel's border, the army said.
   The violence came as Secretary of State George P. Shultz arrived
in Cairo for talks with President Hosni Mubarak, continuing his
efforts aimed at starting Arab-Israeli peace talks and helping
restore calm in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   But the bloodshed has increased since he arrived Thursday on the
five-day mission. At least 11 Palestinians have been killed and
dozens more wounded in the occupied lands in the period.
   Israel's 24-member Cabinet debated the violence on Sunday, and
Israel radio said Transportation Minister Chaim Corfu proposed
closing the West Bank and Gaza to media coverage. No decision was
reported on the issue.
   Israeli soldiers on Sunday sealed the West Bank village of Abud,
20 miles northwest of Jerusalem, where the two Arabs were killed
Saturday night. They twice turned away a reporter who tried to talk
to witnesses.
   Army spokesmen said the shootings were being investigated.
   The Arab-run Palestinian Press Service said Jewish settlers had
tried to enter the village after nightfall and were turned away by
the 3,000 residents.
   Soldiers arrived about 8 p.m. and clashed with villagers who
hurled stones. They fired flares to provide light and later opened
fire with live ammunition, the agency said.
   Israel radio said Arab demonstrators blocked a main highway
outside the village and stoned Israeli soldiers. It said a number
of Jewish settlers also arrived on the scene. Shots were fired, and
the army was investigating the source of the gunfire, Israel radio
added.
   The Palestine Press identified the two dead as Raed Mahmoud Awad
Barghouti, 17, who was shot in the head, and Ahmed Ibrahim Mustafa
al Barghouti, 22, who was wounded in the stomach.
   The deaths brought to 74 the number of Arabs killed by Israeli
gunfire and beatings since anti-occupation rioting erupted Dec. 8,
according to U.N. figures. Hundreds more have been wounded.
   Before flying to Cairo, Shultz met separately with Shamir and
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, who told reporters the negotiations
were complicated ``but not hopeless'' despite rejections by Jordan
and Syria on Saturday.
   ``Nothing is dead, and nothing is at a dead end. It is a very
complicated issue. It may take time,'' Peres said.
   Shultz' peace plan envisions accelerationg negotiations on
Palestinian self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza, which Israel
seized in the 1967 Middle East war, with the eventual goal of
trading land for peace with the Arabs.
   Jordanian and Syrian leaders told Shultz any peace talks would
have to include the participation of the Palestine Liberation
Organization in an international conference. Israel does not
recognize the PLO.
