<2ND_LINE>AM-Fishing or Living,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Muskegon: To Live, Or Fish?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you care more about fishing than
living, come to Muskegon.
   Muskegon was second to last in Money magazine's ranking of
places to live in the United States.
   But Field and Stream magazine's special edition, the ``1988
Guide to the Best in Freshwater Sport,'' lists Muskegon Lake and
the Muskegon River together as one of the ``25 Favorite Fishing
Trips for '88.''
   The special edition, which won't go on sale until April, offers
anglers tips and tactics for taking big fish.
   ``Bass (largemouths and smallmouths) and walleyes are two
gamefish species anglers will find in particularly good supply on
Muskegon Lake,'' the article says. ``The Muskegon River ...
features one of the finest river fisheries in the state.''
   An article in the July 1987 issue of Money magazine put
Muskegon, a city of about 40,000 on the western side of Michigan's
Lower Penninsula, next to last among the ten worst cities to live
in the country.
   Most vacationing anglers come to Muskegon after salmon,
steelhead, bass and walleye, Field and Stream says.
   Walleye _ and Muskegon Lake's reputation as a trophy spot for
them _ are fast approaching salmon as the area's top tourist draw,
it adds.
   The Manufacturers Walleye Council, a group of touring
professional anglers, has chosen Muskegon Lake as the site for its
final regular-season points tournament for 1988.
   As many as 200 two-person teams will pay $200 each to vie for
the $7,000 first prize in the Aug. 27-28 tourney, which offers a
purse of $32,000.
   Muskegon professional walleye guide Mark Martin said that last
year he took more than 60 walleyes weighing more than 9 pounds.
</TEXT>
