<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DietStudy     02-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diet Study,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fragmentary Diet Studies Confuse Food-For-Health Views, Says
Expert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fad health diets and ``marketplace gimmickry''
are giving Americans a distorted view of the type and amount of
foods needed to help prevent chronic disease, according to a
Cornell University professor.
   In a paper prepared for congressional testimony on Tuesday, T.
Colin Campbell said isolated studies, taken out of context and
promoted by special economic interests, often trigger changes in
the American diet that may actually be harmful.
   ``Too many Americans believe in magic bullets. Too many
corporations believe in profit-rich products with very specific
health claims,'' said Campbell.
   Such ``marketplace gimmickry,'' he said, does not help Americans
avoid the so-called ``diseases of affluence'' of osteoporosis and
heart attack.
   In a paper prepared for the Senate governmental affairs
committee, Campbell recommended that the government establish a
national research center to collect and analyze nutrition
information so Americans can receive more accurate information on
diet and health.
   Campbell directed a massive study of the diet and lifestyle of
6,500 persons in 130 locations in the People's Republic of China in
an effort to determine how nutrition affects such diseases as
cancer and heart attack.
   He said the study is not yet finished, but results so far cast
doubt on some of the popular American beliefs about nutrition and
health.
   Among his observations:
   _American studies have shown that a serum cholesterol reading of
180 milligrams per decaliter can reduce the risk of heart attack.
Yet, another U.S. study showed that a reduction in cholesterol
raises the risk of colon cancer. Campbell said that in China, the
cholesterol levels are far below the typical American level, and
the incidence of colon cancer also is low. This shows, he said,
that the study showing an increase in colon cancer with lower
cholesterol ``is an experimental aberration.''
   _Excess calories may not be the sole cause of obesity, Campbell
said. He said the Chinese consume about 20 percent more calories
than do Americans, yet obesity is rare among the Chinese. He said
Chinese average only about 15 percent of their calories in the form
of fat _ far below the typical American.
   _Some American studies have suggested that an increase in fiber
in the diet may lead to a loss of minerals. Campbell said the
Chinese consume about 34 grams of fiber per day, versus about 10
grams for most Americans, and yet the Chinese show healthy levels
of iron, zinc and magnesium, all important minerals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880228-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-LaborMarket     02-28 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Labor Market,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beijing City Opens Labor Market for Those Seeking New Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 people, trying to buck the Chinese
system of assigned jobs for life, gathered Sunday at the opening of
Beijing's first citywide labor market.
   A mostly young crowd, bundled up in heavy greatcoats, peered at
job description posters lining the street and discussed work
opportunities with representatives of 22 factories and companies
who manned desks inside the ``Labor Exchange Center.''
   The center, said deputy chief Zhao Fenyong, was set up by the
city Labor Bureau to carry out the government policy of allowing
people to find jobs more suitable to their needs and skills.
   Those who pay a fee of 27 cents will have their names placed on
the center's computerized list and receive help in finding a new
job, he said.
   Liu Wanxin, of the Tienma Service Co., which supplies tourist
items to department stores, said many people want to find new work
closer to their homes.
   ``Others just don't like their present jobs,'' he said, adding
that his company found seven prospective new employees Sunday
morning.
   Li Hongjun, 34, said she was applying for a job with a Beijing
wine company because it has night shifts, allowing her to care for
a sick sister during the day. She said she could also take a bus to
the winery, rather than commute by bicycle as she does to her
current job.
   A personnel officer at Qinghua University, which is looking for
nine cooks, electricians, drivers and other workers, said factory
workers are attracted to the school's long summer and winter
holidays. Many, said Wang Jingxiang, also want their children to
attend the excellent kindergarten and primary schools run by the
university.
   Since the 1949 communist takeover, Chinese have had little
choice in determining their career.
   Under a system known as ``fen pei,'' Chinese were assigned a job
for life from which they could not be fired, but neither could they
leave.
   High school and elementary school graduates were assigned work
in local businesses or, if they come from the countryside, were
generally returned to the land to farm with the rest of their
family.
   College graduates, a scarce resource here, were sent anywhere in
the country that needed them. A student, majoring in English
literature at prestigious Beijing University, could, for example,
wind up in barren Qinghai province, teaching English to barely
literate peasants.
   But in recent years, cracks have appeared in China's ``iron rice
bowl'' as the country has sought to speed its economic development.
   The Chinese government has recognized that its traditional labor
system has deadened worker creativity and kept workers from fully
using their talents.
   It also has split families, especially those of the educated
classes. Indeed, it is not unusual for couples with college
educations to be assigned jobs in different provinces, thousands of
miles away from one another.
   As a result, China has begun loosening restrictions on
job-hopping and encouraging the 20 million people who have gone off
on their own to set up small private businesses.
   However, the work units to which each Chinese is assigned still
regard employees as the property of the unit and often refuse a job
transfer or exact compensation for the loss of a worker.
   Engineers, scientists and other trained people in particular
have had difficulty leaving their old jobs because of their value
to the work unit.
   That creates the ironic condition that the better one does one's
job here, the less of a chance one has to leave it for something
better.
   ``It's true that if a person has a position of responsibility it
will be more difficult for him to change jobs,'' said the center's
Zhao. ``But if his work unit refuses to let him go, we will do what
we can to help, including assist in finding a replacement.''
   Similar labor markets have appeared at the city district level
in Beijing, but the center that opened Sunday is the first to cover
the entire city.
   Illegal work markets have also sprung up in Beijing and in
several other Chinese cities. Their purpose generally is not to
help employed people find a new job, but to help unemployed
peasants enter the urban labor force, allowing them to abandon the
difficult life in China's countryside.
   Zhao said the city-wide labor market will also stay open in the
evenings and on Sundays to accommodate people who have difficulty
getting away from their jobs to look for new ones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880228-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Zhang     02-28 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Zhang,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Of Shanghai In China's Independent Catholic Church Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Zhang Jiashu, bishop of Shanghai under
China's independent Catholic Church, has died at the age of 96, the
official Xinhua News Agency reported Sunday.
   Mass was said Saturday for Zhang, who died Thursday, at the
Xujiahui Cathedral in Shanghai, the city's largest, the agency said.
   Among those attending where Zong Huaide, bishop of Jinan diocese
and chairman of the China Patriotic Catholic Association.
   The ``Patriotic'' Catholic Church in China broke with the
Vatican in 1957 after accusing Rome of interfering in China's
internal affairs. The church claims more than 3 million followers
in China.
   Xinhua said Zhang studied in Britain and France for 10 years
before returning to China in 1924. In 1960, he was elected bishop
of the Shanghai diocese, which has an estimated 100,000
parishioners and about 20 churches.
   The report said he was vice chairman of the China Patriotic
Catholic Association, director of the National Administrative
Commission of the Catholic Church and a member of the standing
committee of the national committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference.
   Shanghai's more famous bishop is Ignatius Kung, who was
imprisoned for 30 years on treason charges stemming from his
refusal to sever his ties with the Vatican. When Kung, then 84, was
released in 1985, he went to see Zhang, kissed his ring and
promised to act under his guidance.
</TEXT>
