<DOCNO> AP880228-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-Primer Bjt   02-28 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Primer, Bjt,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Process Traces Back To English System Of Removing
Cruel Kings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Arizona Senate opens Gov. Evan
Mecham's impeachment trial Monday, it will embark on a course laid
out in England as a way to remove cruel kings and brought to
America in Colonial days as a way to protect democracy.
   But despite the long and sometimes colorful history of
impeachment, legal scholars say the seldom-used laws are ill
defined. Arizona lawmakers grappling with Mecham's fate have to
make up many rules as they go along.
   ``The Arizona Constitution provides few standards or procedures
for how the Senate is to perform its role,'' said University of
Arizona law professor Robert Glennon.
   Mecham was impeached Feb. 5 by the Arizona House of
Representatives on allegations of concealing a $350,000 campaign
loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart
an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state
official.
   The impeachment amounts to an indictment, and the Senate process
to a trial. The 30 senators will act as both judge and jury for the
embattled Republican governor.
   But an impeachment trial is not a criminal trial _ it's purely
part of the political system. The only penalty the governor faces
is removal from office.
   ``It's basically _ `You're fired,''' Glennon said. ``Impeachment
is a way to get out of office those officials that violate the
public trust.''
   Even before Mecham's impeachment trial begins, political
arguments arising from the legal vagueness have abounded in the
Republican-controlled Senate.
   While setting the rules, the senators have agreed, for example,
that the evidence against Mecham must be ``clear and convincing''
in order to find him guilty. That's not as rigid as the requirement
in criminal trials that guilt be ``beyond a reasonable doubt,'' but
it is tougher than the civil standard of a ``preponderance of the
evidence'' _ more than half _ for a verdict.
   ``There is nothing in the constitution about that and the
senators can do whatever they want,'' Glennon said.
   ``It's typical of the constitution to leave things so open. `Due
process' and `equal protection' are very vague words but we have
thousands and thousands of cases that define what they mean. In
impeachment, we have so few cases, it's not always clear,'' he said.
   Senators are constitutionally required ``to do justice according
to law and evidence.''
   Even the definition of an impeachable offense has been argued
through history.
   Former President Richard Nixon, whose Watergate activities were
probed by an impeachment committee in the U.S. House of
Representatives, argued that a misdeed had to be dastardly enough
to deserve a criminal indictment to be impeachable.
   But that's not necessarily true, Glennon said. Impeachment
doesn't have to involve illegal activities _ only ``high crimes,
misdemeanors, or malfeasance'' in Arizona.
   No court in Arizona has specifically defined high crimes and
misdemeanors regarding impeachment, but the Arizona Supreme Court
has said malfeasance occurs if an elected official commits ``an act
which is either positively wrong or unlawful,'' according to
Arizona Supreme Court Chief Justice Frank Gordon.
   The trial may look to observers like a criminal trial, but all
30 senators will have a chance to question witnesses, much like a
congressional hearing. A two-thirds vote _ 20 senators _ is
required to convict the governor.
   Gordon, the chief justice, will sit as a referee and be called
the ``presiding officer.'' Five members of the House, through their
attorneys, will sit as the ``Board of Managers'' and handle the
prosecution. Mecham will have his own defense attorneys.
   And there won't be any attempt to have an impartial jury.
   ``It is quite clear that the framers of the U.S. Constitution
(from which the Arizona law is drawn) chose to make the Senate as
judge and jury,'' Glennon said. ``The governor has no right to 12
ignorant lay people in this deal. In impeachment, there is no
intent to have an impartial jury. The framers thought the fact that
the senators would know something about the case was good.''
   Mecham also has been indicted in state district court on six
felony counts involving the $350,000 loan, which amounted to about
a third of his campaign war chest, and faces a criminal trial March
22. He faces a recall election May 17.
   He is the 16th governor to be impeached in U.S. history; six
have been convicted and removed from office. He is the first
Arizona governor to be impeached.
   If convicted by the Senate, Mecham would be succeeded by
Secretary of State Rose Mofford, a Democrat who is acting governor
pending the impeachment trial's outcome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880228-0036 </DOCNO>
