<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CigaretteSuit     02-28 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cigarette Suit,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cigarette Suit Evidence Has A Common Thread: Lawyers Usually Cast
Shadows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During the first month of a cigarette
liability trial, anti-tobacco attorneys have introduced stacks of
documents and presented 10 witnesses. Through much of the evidence
runs a common thread: lawyers and more lawyers.
   Attorneys for the plaintiff argue that cigarette company
attorneys kept a keen eye on smoking and health research, helped
shape corporate policy and vetoed putting safer smokes on the
market.
   One reason, according to the plaintiff's theory, is because the
companies felt that if they acknowledged the dangers of smoking _
either through public statements or marketing of a less dangerous
product _ they would be open to lawsuits over existing cigarettes.
   The trial of Philip Morris Co., Liggett Group Inc. and Lorillard
Inc., makers of the brands that Rose Cipollone smoked for 40 years
before she died of lung cancer at the age of 58 in 1984, enters its
second month Monday. Her husband, Antonio, is pursuing a suit she
filed before she died and is asking for unspecified damages.
   Attorneys for the tobacco companies say legal concerns did not
dictate research.
   ``Lawyers are involved in decisions of industry all over the
place,'' said Chuck Wall, an attorney for the Kansas City, Mo., of
firm Shook, Hardy & Bacon, which represents Morris and Lorillard.
   He said lawyers need to be familiar with research and scientific
developments because of the rising tide of lawsuits against the
cigarette-makers since the early 1950s and to advise clients on
advertising and testimony before public bodies.
   The evidence so far has addressed three of the plaintiffs'
allegations _ that the defendants knew how to make a safer
cigarette but didn't; knew of potential health hazards from the
1920s through 1940s but did not act enough on the knowledge and
failed to tell consumers; and sought to suppress or shape in their
favor research on the hazards of smoking.
   The jury has heard the testimony of former in-house and external
researchers, top corporate executives and an expert on smoking and
health.
   Testimony during most of last week was from Joseph F. Cullman
III, chairman emeritus and former president of Philip Morris.
   Marc Z. Edell, representing the Cipollone estate, asked Cullman,
for example, if the company's general counsel ``advised'' him on
cigarette smoking and health issues.
   ``He wouldn't advise,'' Cullman said. ``He would monitor them,
I'd say.''
   Several confidential documents introduced into evidence Thursday
appear to indicate the role of lawyers.
   A letter dated April 29, 1974, from the chairman of R.J.
Reynolds to an official of the Council for Tobacco Research,
describes a committee of manufacturers formed to study
industry-funded research programs. The council itself was funded by
tobacco companies.
   The Reynolds executive named the committee's chairman as David
R. Hardy, the named partner in the Shook, Hardy firm handling the
current trial.
   A July 3, 1974, memo to committee members from another Shook,
Hardy attorney speaks of ``gaps in knowledge'' in the
smoking-health field.
   Included is mention of a paper by tobacco council lawyer Ed
Jacob with a section described as ``a summarization and slight
updating of research recommendations.''
   Before Hardy assumed control of the manufacturers' research
study committee, he corresponded with a tobacco council scientist,
another memo showed.
   A Dec. 24, 1969, letter indicates the researcher, Arthur Furst,
had discussed with Jacob the work of a British cancer researcher.
   Furst recommended to Hardy that the British researcher, H.J.
Eysenck, a psychologist at the Bethlem Royal and Maudsley hospitals
in London, be given money for a pilot project. The letter said
Eysenck had a theory that ``there may be a relationship between the
appearance of cancer for some people and their emotional make up.''
   Twelve years later, Eysenck wrote to Jacob to ask for more
research council funding, although it is unclear from the letter,
also introduced last week, what the project involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
