<HEAD>Thousands Protest Police Ineffectiveness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several thousand people marched though
Madrid's main streets on Sunday to protest the failure of police to
protect citizens from petty crime and get drugs out of the schools.
   The rally organized by numerous civic and neighborhood groups
drew 10,000 people, said Enrique Castro, spokesman for the
organizers. Police said the march drew 5,000 people.
   Citizen groups for years have criticized the government of
Socialist Prime Minsiter Felipe Gonzalez for failing to stem a
sharp increase in petty crime and drug trafficking. Last week,
Gonzalez said there were plans to hire more police.
   The marchers protested drug trafficking in schools and said the
government's plans to beef up police ranks were inadequate.
   Police have made several drug sweeps in the nation's schools as
media attention has focused on the problem and on the rise in crime.
</TEXT>
