<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SealedCourthouse     02-28 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sealed Courthouse,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brevard County Courthouse Sealed After High Levels of Asbestos
Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Brevard County Courthouse has been
ordered sealed and workers were being relocated to shopping centers
and hotels following the discovery of extremely high levels of
asbestos.
   Brevard Circuit Judge Dean Moxley ordered the closing Saturday
after Asbestos Technologies Inc. reported asbestos levels as high
as 3.642 fibers per cubic centimeter in the office of Judge Gil
Goshorn.
   Levels were as high as 0.182 in hearing rooms used by Goshorn
and Judge Charles Harris, said County Administrator Tom Jenkins.
   The U.S. Occupational Safety and Heath Administration consider
levels of 0.2 to be unsafe and warrant evacuation. Acceptable
levels normally fall below 0.1.
   ``3.642 is absolutely alarming. The courthouse is not fit for
human occupation without protection,'' said Moxley, who moved his
office and staff to a courthouse annex last week after levels of
0.175 were reported in his office.
   ``ATI said it's probably the worst reading they have ever
encountered,'' he said.
   Moxley's order prohibits anyone from removing any items,
including civil and criminal files, and traffic, child support and
land records stored in the courthouse, without going through a
cleansing room. Violators will be held in contempt of court, said
County Commission Chairwoman Sue Schmitt.
   ATI officials planned Sunday to test courthouse records for
asbestos. Test results were expected Monday or Tuesday, she said.
   Meanwhile, officials tried to set up temporary quarters while a
decision is made on what to do with the building.
   The murder trial of Christopher Scott Lawrence, scheduled to
begin Monday before Harris, will be held at the North Brevard
Service Complex, officials said.
   County Judge Peter Haddad planned to set up offices in a board
room at the North Brevard Service Complex and circuit judges Harris
and Goshorn were to be moved to the Titusville Quality Inn.
   The State Attorney's Office was being moved to the Southern Bell
building.
   The Clerk of County and Circuit Courts Office will have a
skeleton crew at the Gibson School Gymnasium to direct other
employees.
   ``The rest of our employees will be furloughed until we see what
is going on. We can't get access to any of our records and that's
our biggest problem,'' said Harry Bennett, chief deputy of the
clerk of county and circuit courts.
   ATI workers will be setting up a ``cocoon'' made of plastic
sheeting on the first and second floors of the courthouse building,
enabling operations there to resume later this week, Jenkins said.
   Brevard-Seminole State Attorney Norm Wolfinger said his staff
would probably remain in the Southern Bell building for up to six
months.
</TEXT>
