<HEAD>Two Norwegian Peacekeepers Wounded in Mine Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Norwegian soldiers serving with the
U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon were wounded in a mine explosion
in a southern Lebanese village on Sunday, U.N. spokesman Timur
Goksel said.
   He said both soldiers underwent surgery at a U.N. field hospital
in the border town of Naqoura. A Norwegian officer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the leg of one of the soldiers had to
be amputated.
   Goksel said the mine exploded at 3:25 p.m. near the soldiers'
position in Blat, in Israel's self-proclaimed security zone. The
zone overlaps with the peacekeeping force's area of operations in
south Lebanon.
   He would not disclose the peacekeepers' ranks or names, pending
notification of their families.
   Norway has an 881-man contingent serving with the nine-nation,
5,800-strong peacekeeping force. They were deployed in 1978 after a
brief Israeli incursion into south Lebanon.
