<1ST_LINE>r p AM-YoungKennedy     02-28 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Young Kennedy,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Kennedy Works For Father's Re-election, Considers Own
Political Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casually dressed and moving easily on his
artificial limb, Edward M. Kennedy Jr. greeted Democratic activists
at the core of the Kennedy family's political base, a union hall in
a heavily Irish-Catholic section of Boston.
   The younger Kennedy's first priority is winning re-election for
his father to the U.S. Senate. But as to the inevitable questions
about his own political future, he admitted Saturday he is getting
``good practical experience.''
   Kennedy, 26, resigned his position as head of Facing the
Challenge, Inc., a non-profit group he founded in 1985 devoted to
eliminating barriers for the physically and mentally disabled.
   As co-chairman of his father's fifth re-election campaign along
with his sister Kara, Kennedy spends all his working time at
campaign headquarters or on the road across Massachusetts, meeting
local supporters, drumming up new backers and fighting to get
people excited about a race which to date has only one candidate.
   ``Whether my father draws a strong opponent or a weak opponent,
it's still necessary for him to know what's going on in different
communities and for my father to be able to tell people what he's
done for Massachusetts,'' Kennedy said.
   When news of Ted Jr.'s involvement in the campaign became known
last fall, observers assumed the post amounted to a training ground
for the younger Kennedy to seek political office.
   Kennedy said Saturday he has not decided whether to return to
Facing the Challenge after the Senate campaign concludes. And while
he didn't rule out seeking office, he said he has no specific plans.
   ``If you're asking me, am I going to be involved and active in
my community, the answer is yes,'' said Kennedy, who lives in
Boston. ``I am always going to be active and concerned about issues.
   ``I don't have any plans right now... I'm concentrating on my
father's re-election.'' But he added, ``It is good, practical
experience.''
   Kennedy got some good, practical experience in Boston's
Dorchester section Saturday where he attended a state Democratic
party caucus at Florian Hall, home of one of Boston's firefighters
union locals. Democrats of Irish descent formed the backbone of
John F. Kennedy's political base in the 1940s and the Kennedy
family appears to have held onto that popularity.
   ``Anybody in the Kennedy family has his head on straight,'' said
Camilla Duffy of Dorchester, who is gathering nomination signatures
for the Senator's re-election campaign.
   Many of the roughly 100 Democratic activists recognized Kennedy
from his work for the disabled and greeted him warmly.
   Kennedy lost his right leg above the knee to cancer in 1973. He
has remained active in skiing, swimming and weight lifting.
   ``I'm lucky to be alive,'' Kennedy said. His own return to a
full and active life, he said, was all too exceptional. ``There are
other people who don't have the same opportunities.''
   State Democratic party Chairman Chester Atkins, also attending
the caucus, said Democrats would welcome a campaign by the younger
Kennedy. ``He's been a great campaigner. He cares deeply about
people,'' Atkins said. And as for Kennedy's political career, ``I
have to assume he'll have the opportunity.''
   Joseph Kennedy II gained some attention before running for
office by saying he was unsure of the ability of government to help
people _ a position he modified after his election to Congress. On
that score, Edward Kennedy Jr. said he has no doubts.
   ``I am one who really believes that public service is an
honorable profession. It's what my whole family has believed. I've
had a couple of uncles who gave their lives for public service.
   ``People who think they don't have a say _ I really reject that.
They can, whether in this hall or a parish, a homeless shelter,''
Kennedy said.
</TEXT>
