<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1505EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     02-28 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor's Impeachment Trial Opens Monday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham-Primer Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen months afer he grasped his
long-sought prize, the governorship of Arizona, Evan Mecham returns
to the state Capitol from exile Monday for a Senate impeachment
trial which could end his political life.
   In recent days, Mecham has battled to stop the trial. He has
said that his constitutional rights are being violated. He hired
new lawyers who petitioned senators and the state Supreme Court to
halt the proceedings.
   But the Senate would tolerate no delays, and the Supreme Court
said it could not breach the separation of powers doctrine by
interfering in a legislative matter.
   ``The people of this state should be as scared and frightened as
all get-out,'' Mecham, 63, said at a weekend news conference.
``This isn't Ev Mecham's rights we're talking about. This is basic
rights in the state of Arizona.''
   The conservative Republican governor renewed his vow that he
would not take the easy way out and resign.
   ``My resignation would write a bad chapter in the history of
Arizona,'' he said as he stood before reporters in down home
western garb: boots, blue jeans, a powder blue jacket, plaid shirt
and a string tie with a huge silver and torquoise clasp.
   ``That would be giving in to the powers who have schemed and
planned to put so much pressure on me that I would eventually
resign,'' he said.
   Mecham insisted he should be allowed to resolve a March 22
criminal trial before the impeachment trial and its publicity.
   ``As governor of the state, I ask nothing more than is accorded
to any garden variety criminal,'' he said of the due process rights
he demanded. ``I certainly do not think that as governor I should
be accorded anything less.''
   Some members of the Senate suspected that what Mecham really
wanted was to delay the impeachment trial until after his scheduled
May 17 recall election, hoping for an outpouring of support from
constituents who elected him on his fifth try for the office.
   But the 30-member Senate refused to allow any delay.
   ``We've got to get going. The people of Arizona deserve a fair
break and the fair break is that the trial moves forward,'' said
Senate Democratic Minority Leader Alan Stephens.
   To convict Mecham, two-thirds of the senators must find that
Mecham committed ``high crimes, misdemeanors or malfeasance in
office.''
   Upon conviction, the Senate could bar him from ever holding
public office again.
   Although Mecham is best known outside Arizona for a series of
public gaffes and outrageous comments which offended many minority
groups, he is not on trial for those acts.
   Mecham is charged with three misdeeds _ concealing a $350,000
campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund
by loaning it to his car dealership and trying to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official.
   The House of Representatives, which impeached Mecham Feb. 5,
detailed the allegations in 23 articles of impeachment, the
equivalent of an indictment in a criminal case.
   After his impeachment, Mecham was required to step aside as
governor pending outcome of the trial. However, he is still
addressed as governor and draws his regular salary. He set up
offices in suburban Glendale in what he calls his ``government in
exile.''
   Secretary of State Rose Mofford is acting governor in his place.
   Frank X. Gordon, chief justice of the Arizona Supreme Court, who
will preside over the impeachment trial, has called it ``perhaps
the most important proceeding in the history of Arizona.''
   ``Clearly these are volatile times,'' Gordon said. ``Perhaps
never in Arizona history have so many of our citizens had such
fervent beliefs on a given subject. We should be thankful that our
system of government is equipped to peacefully and fairly resolve
such a volatile situation. It is up to all of us as citizens to let
the system work.''
</TEXT>
