<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia Bjt   02-28 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Continues Personal Involvement in Armenian Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev met with two prominent
Armenian writers in an unusual personal campaign to allay concerns
of Armenians demanding annexation of land in a neighboring
republic, two activists said Sunday.
   The writers, Silva Kaputikyan and Zori Balayan, met with the
Soviet leader on Friday, said Sergei Grigoryants, a Moscow-based
dissident, and Hovik Vassilian, an Armenian activist and editor of
the underground journal, The Armenian Matter.
   They said the writers met Thursday with Politburo member and
propaganda chief Alexander N. Yakovlev.
   ``Gorbachev said he'd take the matter under his personal control
and see to it that it gets the proper attention,'' Vassilian quoted
Kaputikyan as saying of the meeting with the Soviet leader.
Vassilian spoke in a telephone interview from Yerevan, the capital
of the Armenian republic.
   The official media carried no report on the Gorbachev meeting.
   It was the second time that Gorbachev had become involved in the
sensitive Armenian dispute, which erupted last week into street
demonstrations that witnesses said involved thousands of protesters.
   On Friday, Gorbachev appealed for ``civil maturity and
restraint'' in an address read on Armenian television by a senior
party official. In the address, Gorbachev promised that the
Communist Party Central Committee would review relations among the
Soviet Union's more than 100 nationalities.
   Until now, the 56-year-old leader had never injected himself
into an ethnic dispute since becoming party general secretary in
March 1985.
   He may have stepped in now as a defense of his policy of
``glasnost,'' or openness on social issues.
   Vassilian said that organizers of last week's massive protests
in Yerevan announced Friday they would hold no more protests until
March 26 so national authorities could have time to review the
dispute.
   The unrest has focused on the Delaware-sized region of
Nagorno-Karabakh, in the Caucasus Mountains. The region is inside
the republic of Azerbaidzhan, but Armenians want it to be annexed
to their republic.
   More than 80 percent of Nagorno-Karabakh's 157,000 residents are
Aremenian.
   The official news agency Tass and central Soviet television on
Saturday tried to calm the population and play down reports of
ethnic trouble by taking up the theme of brotherhood.
   They carried interviews with ethnic Armenians and Azerbaidzhanis
saying they live together in harmony and that it was important for
everyone to return to their jobs.
   The media said some workers in Yerevan even showed up
voluntarily for work Sunday, their day off, to make up for time
lost while they were away from their jobs demonstrating.
   Grigoryants and other witnesses said hundreds of thousands of
Armenians took to the streets of Yerevan last week to press their
demands after the ruling Politburo rejected an annexation proposal.
   The decision to hold off on more protests apparently was a
result of Gorbachev's address and of an Armenian Central Committee
decision to ask for a review of the dispute by national leaders.
   Vassilian said about 150,000 demonstrators gathered Saturday on
Yerevan streets to continue the protest, but he said the city was
calm Sunday.
   Armenian activists have sent a lengthy report to the central
government in Moscow outlining why they believe Nagorno-Karabakh
should be made part of Armenia, Vassilian said.
   Grigoryants said that during a two-day visit to Yerevan, he
learned that ethnic Russians had been brought in to replace the
mostly Armenian local militia force and that 28 planeloads of
soldiers had been flown into the capital to help keep order.
   At one point last week, Grigoryants said, workers at the state
broadcasting authority, Gostelradio, threatened to stop all
transmissions unless soldiers were withdrawn from broadcast studios.
   The workers also demanded the right to broadcast reports on the
demonstrations. Within a day, the soldiers were pulled out of the
studios and reports on the demonstrations appeared on Armenian
television, Grigoryants said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
