<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1532EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Stoogemania Bjt   02-28 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stoogemania, Bjt,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pies Fly, Flicks Roll As Stooge Fans Gather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cream pies flew, old flicks rolled and fans
talked to to an old Three Stooges supporting actor when about 1,000
die-hard fans of the celebrated knuckleheads gathered for a weekend
of _ nyuk, nyuk _ Stoogemania.
   ``I've loved Larry, Moe and Curly ever since I was 5 years
old,'' said Virginia Riviera, 30, who came with two friends from
Salem, Mass.
   They and others swapped memorabilia, threw pies and watched such
films as ``Three Little Pigskins,'' ``All the World's a Stooge,''
``Dizzy Doctors'' and ``Disorder in the Court.''
   ``I'd go anywhere there's a Three Stooges convention,'' said
Riviera, ``as long as I don't have to fly.''
   Curly impersonator David Knight ``was involved in everything,''
Joe Jerrier, one of the convention's organizers, said Sunday.
``When he showed up the place was just jammed.''
   Knight, an iron worker from Palmyra, N.Y., who bears a pate much
like his cinematic hero's, tweaked ears and performed Curly's
outrageous antics to the delight of fans who came from as far away
as San Francisco for the two-day exercise in Stoogery.
   Jerrier said nostalgia has sparked a resurgence of interest in
an act famous for head-knocking, face-slapping, belly-butting
slapstick, pratfalls and endless buffoonery.
   The original Three Stooges, created in the vaudeville days of
the 1920s, were Morris ``Moe'' Horowitz, who later changed his last
name to Howard; his brother Samuel ``Shemp,'' and Larry Fineberg,
a.k.a. Fine.
   By the early '30s, Shemp had left in a pay dispute and Jerome
``Curly,'' another Horowitz brother, took over.
   The Stooges made more than 190 short films and about 50
feature-length films until the '60s, said Jerrier. Moe was the last
Stooge to die, in 1975.
   In one room, Three Stooges postcards, T-shirts, belts, ceramic
masks and hand puppets were displayed on tables.
   Also on display were books, publicity stills, movie posters and
a canceled check from Moe. A Stooge trivia contest was in progress
when the pie fight _ a highlight of the event _ broke out.
   ``I was emcee and I didn't even get a chance to close my eyes,''
said Jerrier, 37, a firefighter from Gardiner, Maine. ``I got four
of 'em.''
   A telephone call was placed to Emil Sitka and fans were allowed
to chat with the man who played a host of older men's roles in more
than 60 Stooge films.
   Sitka, who is in his 70s and now lives in Camarillo, Calif., was
one of the few actors who played alongside Shemp as well as Curly,
said Jerrier, who claims one of the country's largest videocassette
collections of Stooge flicks.
   Jerrier said Shemp quit because each of the Stooges was making
$100 a week while their manager earned $2,000.
   The convention raised more than $4,000 by Sunday afternoon for
cancer research, said Jerrier. Ron Eugley, another organizer, said
at least 1,000 fans showed up.
   In addition to footage from Stooge films, fans were treated to
rare footage of Curly's wedding, Moe barbecuing, the Stooges in
baseball uniforms in the Chicago Cubs dugout in 1938, and on the
Queen Mary in 1939.
   George Likar said he's been a member of the national Three
Stooges Fan Club since 1985.
   ``I got hooked 10 years ago, watching them on TV,'' said Likar,
who flew in from Joliet, Ill. ``The Stooges are great! Curly's my
favorite. He gets to do all the things I wish I could do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
