<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Guerrillas     02-28 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Guerrillas,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Sink Palestinian Guerrilla Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's navy sank a boat carrying
Palestinian guerrillas who were planning an attack against Israel,
killing two Arabs on board, police said Sunday.
   An Israeli patrol intercepted the vessel off the southern
Lebanese port city of Tyre shortly after nightfall on Saturday,
police said. Three of the five guerillas on board swam to safety
and were captured, they said.
   Police said the squad belonged to the Libyan-backed Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, which is
based in Damascus, Syria.
   But Fatah, the Palestine Liberation Organization's mainstream
guerrilla faction, said the guerrillas were Fatah members.
   Fatah sources in Sidon, provincial capital of south Lebanon,
said the squad had planned to attack the northern Israeli coastal
town of Nahariya to avenge the killing of three PLO officers in
Cyprus two weeks ago.
   The PLO had blamed the Feb. 14 car bombing in Limassol, Cyprus,
on Israel's secret service, Mossad. The victims were identified as
Col. Marwan Kayyali, Lt. Col. Mohammed Sultan and Lt. Col. Mohammed
Buheis.
   Police in Tyre who interrogated the surviving guerrillas quoted
them as saying they belonged to the Popular Front, which is headed
by former Syrian army captain Ahmed Jibril.
   The front claimed responsibility for a Dec. 26 attack on an army
base in northern Israel by a guerrilla who flew a motorized
hang-glider across the border from Lebanon. Six Israeli soldiers
were killed and eight wounded by hand grenades and gunfire before
the attacking guerrilla was shot and killed.
   Israel radio reported Sunday that Palestinian guerrilla
organizations and anti-Israel Lebanese militia groups were
developing small navies to infiltrate Israel. It said guerrillas
receive their training in Arab countries and eastern Europe.
   The Israeli navy carries out routine patrols off the Lebanese
coast, frequently stopping and searching suspicious vessels.
   On Dec. 11, guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Shiite Hezbollah, or
Party of God, organization opened fire on an Israeli patrol vessel,
killing one soldier. The Israeli boat sank the Hezbollah craft, and
four militiamen drowned.
   Three years ago, an Israeli navy vessel sunk a ship carrying 28
guerrillas who the navy said were on their way to attack targets
inside Israel.
</TEXT>
