<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Summit 1stLd-Writethru a0741 02-28 0970</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Summit Has Roots In Reykjavik</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 17th graf, NATO has, to correct style on plural of forum
to forums, sted fora; SUBS last graf, At their, to fix time to this
week, sted next week</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seeds of this week's summit meeting at
NATO's sprawling headquarters were planted nearly 16 months ago
when President Reagan faced Mikhail S. Gorbachev across a plain
wooden table in a house in Iceland and seemed to forget Western
Europe's interests.
   It was October 12, 1986, and as dusk crept over the windows at
Hofdi House in Reykjavik and the whole world waited, Reagan and
Gorbachev got into a hot negotiation about the possibility of
scrapping all their nuclear missiles.
   They failed. But when details of the talks came out, Western
European allies who had depended on a no-surprise U.S. defense and
arms control style for 39 years wondered if Reagan had forgotten to
take their needs into consideration.
   ``We don't think it's a fair accusation,'' said a Reagan
administration official. ``We've consulted with the allies
assiduously before and after Reykjavik, but there's no denying the
perception is there among Europeans that the U.S. was willing to
make drastic reductions in nuclear weapons, over their heads.''
   ``The summit in Brussels will give them a bully pulpit to get
their views across,'' said the official, one of several U.S. summit
planners who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
   ``That's not to say we don't want a summit; we think it's
important to have this meeting at this juncture, for sound,
alliance reasons,'' the official said.
   ``It will let President Reagan show that despite some of the
recent dents in his Teflon shield, he is an active and commanding
presence. But on a scale of one to 100, the Europeans want it 60 or
70 and we want it 40 or 30.''
   The Europeans' aim for the first NATO summit since 1982 is not
just to remind Reagan of their interests as he heads for another
meeting with Gorbachev, in Moscow in the spring.
   It is to talk ``through him'' to whoever replaces Reagan as
president next January and to set the stage for what is likely to
be several years of alliance-wide agonizing over the future of its
internal relationships and its dealings with the Soviet Union.
   The leaders will gather at the sprawling NATO headquarters on
the outskirts of Brussels on Wednesday and Thursday. The public
will be barred from all but a brief opening and brief closing
session and several hours have been devoted to meetings without
large numbers of aides.
   At the end, the leaders will issue a declaration summarizing
their goals and ideals for NATO's future. There also is talk of
issuing a separate statement on conventional weapons.
   Rozanne Ridgway, assistant secretary of state, said Sunday that
two summit issues would be: ``how do we stay strong so that we
don't make the world safe for conventional war or invite it'' and
how to get the Soviets to reduce their now-stronger non-nuclear
forces?
   The Europeans fear that with the possibility of a nuclear-free
world, they may end up with no protection against the superior
Soviet forces. Ridgway, interviewed on Cable News Network's
``Newsmaker Sunday,'' said, however, she believes the NATO alliance
will always have ``a combination of conventional and nuclear
deterrents.''
   On an issue prompted partly by domestic budget pressure on
Reagan, Ridgway said the president will take NATO a message on
``burden-sharing,'' NATO jargon for dividing up the manpower and
financial load of maintaining Western defenses. She did not say
what the message would be but said, ``They can do more. We can do
more.''
   Any private understandings at the meeting will be transmitted to
lower-level groups that have been working for months to provide
answers to some of the questions posed by a new climate of
East-West relations ushered in since Gorbachev's accession.
   The leaders are less likely to dwell on the nuts and bolts of
defense and arms control problems facing the alliance in the short
run.
   NATO has already committed itself to a U.S.-Soviet plan to
reduce long-range nuclear weaponry by 50 percent. Granted, there is
still some haggling within NATO on the pace and scope of
negotiations on short-range nuclear forces, chemical weapons and
conventional forces. But the leaders are not expected to spend much
time on these details, leaving those tasks to other officials and
other forums.
   Nor is Reagan expected to get into a general discussion of
problems the United States is having with some of the allies over
the continuation of American base rights. Talks with those
countries _ Portugal, Spain and Greece _ are being handled
elsewhere.
   Beyond the internal problems, perhaps hovering over them, is the
broadest issue of all: the relevancy of the Western alliance at a
time when the Soviet Union is exhibiting signs of major reform and
appears to be more forthcoming than ever in meeting Western demands
_ like one for a withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   The alliance has stuck together for four decades out of fear of
an expansionist and untrustworthy Soviet Union dominated by its
military leaders.
   After nearly three years of Gorbachev and no sign in letup in
the ferment in his country and among some of his allies, NATO
leaders are wondering how their alliance should respond.
   At their summit this week, ``I think it's going to be both a
moment of looking at the success that the alliance has had and
getting down to the hard issues ahead _ the analysis of the current
situation in the Soviet Union, the opportunities it might
present,'' one official said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Gottlieb has covered NATO affairs in
Brussels and Washington since 1980.
</TEXT>
