<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 1556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ShipFire     02-28 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ship Fire,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illegal Aliens Trapped In Hold Set Fire, Are Rescued Unhurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Dominican stowaways who were
locked in the cargo hold of a container ship set a fire to get the
crew's attention, but the blaze burned out of control, the Coast
Guard said.
   Coast Guard spokesman Alan Burd said no one was injured in the
fire aboard the 560-foot Nedlloyd Singapore.
   ``When the ship's crew went in to fight the fire, they found
four Dominicans that had stowed away in the ship's last port of
call,'' he said. ``It appears that the four stowaways set the fire
intentionally to attract the crew's attention because they were
locked in this cargo hold.''
   Burd said the Dominicans were rescued unharmed and turned over
to local police.
   One crew member fell while fighting the fire and appeared to
have broken a leg, but no other injuries were reported.
   The Dominicans boarded the ship Friday night in the Dominican
Republic port of Haina, about 10 miles west of the capital Santo
Domingo, a spokesman for the Puerto Rico Police Department said. It
docked in San Juan early Sunday.
   Burd said the fire was first reported around 2:30 a.m. and raged
out of control about an hour later.
   There was no immediate estimate of damages.
</TEXT>
