<HEAD>Ethiopian Airlines Pilot Trainee Defects to Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ethiopian Airlines pilot trainee
landed a small plane at Khartoum Airport and asked for asylum in
Sudan, an official source said Sunday.
   The source said Gabre Getahon, 22, was handed over to Sudanese
security authorities and the Cessna, which belonged to Ethiopian
Airlines, was under guard at the airport.
   Other sources said Getahon decided to defect to Sudan on
Saturday, while on a training flight in the small aircraft.
   He was quoted as saying that he first planned to land at
ed-Damazin, in southeastern Sudan near the Ethiopian border, but
could not land there because of maintenance operations under way at
the airport. He then followed the Blue Nile to Khartoum Airport,
where he put down the plane.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Getahon is
from Tigre province in northern Ethiopia, where a rebellion has
been going on for years.
   He told Sudanese authorities he fled to escape ``repression'' in
his homeland, the sources said.
   He also reportedly claimed to have made several previous
defection attempts via Kenya before joining the airline but was
caught and returned to Ethiopia.
