<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hardin,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amy Hardin, Liver Transplant Recipient As Infant, Dies at 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAHOKIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amy Lynn Hardin, who underwent a liver
transplant at the tender age of 11 months thanks to vigorous
community fund-raising, has died at the age of 5.
   ``There will never be another one like her, not like my Amy,''
said her mother, Robin Hardin. ``She's at peace now.''
   Amy died at home Saturday. She would have turned 6 on June 1.
   Amy was born with biliary atresia, in which the bile ducts
malfunction and the liver becomes hard. She underwent surgery when
she was 6 weeks old and again at 3 months, but the operations were
unsuccessful.
   Doctors said her only chance for survival was a liver transplant.
   Amy's health became a cause for community residents, who rallied
in late 1982 and early 1983 to raise more than $260,000 for the
transplant.
   The rock group Kiss performed a benefit concert in 1983 at Kiel
Auditorium in St. Louis. That same year, Amy received a letter of
support from President Reagan.
   ``If it wasn't for the community getting together, we wouldn't
have had five years,'' Mrs. Hardin said. ``She was the joy of our
life. She was very strong. She fought all the way to the end.''
   The transplanted liver Amy received on May 10, 1983, began to
fail around Thanksgiving, Mrs. Hardin said.
   On Dec. 11, the family took Amy to the University of Minnesota
Hospital in Minneapolis, where the transplant had been performed.
She returned home Jan. 16 after doctors said her chances for
recovery were not good.
   ``She couldn't stand it anymore,'' Mrs. Hardin said. ``We made a
promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. We brought
her home and the family took turns being with her.''
   Amy's transplant was termed a success, but her recovery was
hampered by a series of setbacks caused by rejection of the new
liver, viruses and side effects from medication.
   ``Doctors like to say that you are over the hump after five
years, but one can never say never. There are just too many
complications,'' Mary Stanik, spokeswoman for University of
Minnesota Hospital, said Saturday.
   Besides her parents, Amy is survived by two brothers.
   Funeral services will be Monday at Holy Family Church in Cahokia.
</TEXT>
