<2ND_LINE>AM-Preschool Molest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0754,0869</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McMartin Trial Into Tenth Month</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `The latest...', to CORRECT to last week,
sted this week. SUBS 19th graf, `The really...', to CLARIFY that
entire quotation is attributed to Gunson.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has been 10 months since the trial began,
seven months since the first witness appeared and an incredible
five years since the McMartin Pre-School molestation case hit the
courts.
   And there is no end in sight.
   Prosecutors say they will conclude their presentation by July,
but the defense isn't saying how long it may take.
   ``Sometimes it irks me when people talk about how long it's
been,'' says defense attorney Dean Gits, one of the players in this
long-running drama on the 15th floor of the downtown Criminal
Courts Building.
   ``This has to be put into perspective. The case is absolutely
unique,'' he said last week. ``We are dealing with allegations that
cover four to five years. Murders don't take that long; it's a
split second. Rapes and robberies don't take that long.
   ``How do you reconstruct a period of time that happened many,
many years ago and covers four to five years? If people don't
understand that then they don't understand why it's taking so
long.''
   Gits represents Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61, who is on trial along
with her son, Raymond Buckey, 29, charged with 100 child
molestations at their now defunct family owned preschool in
suburban Manhattan Beach.
   With time, the case has changed.
   Five teachers originally charged had their cases dismissed for
lack of evidence. The prosecution, which once involved 41 children,
now focuses on 13 youngsters who have grown from toddlers to
pre-teen-agers.
   And the children's sometimes bizarre stories of satan worship,
animal mutilation and trips to remote places have all but vanished.
   ``I sense that they have weeded out those (children) who went
into fantasyland,'' says Gits.
   The latest child witness, a slender, 11-year-old boy, took the
stand last week, telling jurors in 15 minutes what he remembered of
his alleged molestation by Buckey and mentioning briefly that he
once saw Buckey kill a horse.
   In a now familiar pattern, the cross-examination by Gits and
Buckey's attorney, Danny Davis, extended for days as the lawyers
tried to elicit details which the prosecution never sought.
   Details of the horse incident, for example, were almost
impossible to extract from the young witness who repeatedly
answered, ``I don't know.''
   But the boy, nervous and embarrassed, told of being fondled and
forced into oral copulation by Buckey and said he felt ``sick and
dirty'' when he drew pictures of the incident for his mother.
   Davis says he sees a pattern of fading memories. But Deputy
District Attorney Lael Rubin, who has guided the case almost from
its inception, says the child witnesses have improved with age.
   ``The children are more articulate. Their memories may not be as
detailed as several years ago, but they're older, more articulate
and less intimidated,'' she says.
   So far the jurors, who have sworn to stick with the trial no
matter how long it lasts, have heard from only five of the
children. Other prosecution witnesses called so far have included
doctors, police officers and parents.
   ``The really important witnesses are the children themselves,''
says Ms. Rubin's co-counsel, Deputy District Attorney Roger Gunson.
``And the children have testified very well.''
   The trial's duration has had a personal impact on all
participants.
   The jurors, initially restless, have settled into a routine,
taking copious notes. Many of them carry lunchboxes as if they are
going to work.
   ``They've become part of the case and the commitment is coming
through,'' says Gits.
   Gunson jogs and rides a bicycle to relieve tension. Ms. Rubin
and Davis found that they had enrolled in the same health club, and
they often encounter each other working out in preparation for
their courtroom battles.
   Gits shuns exercise, saying, ``When I want to relax I smoke a
cigarette and drink a cup of coffee.''
   The greatest strain is on the defendants. The gray-haired Mrs.
Buckey, free on bail, sits and knits during recesses, chats with
courtroom spectators or thumbs through a small Bible.
   ``She has her faith and believes very much that God has helped
carry her through this,'' says Gits.
   Her son, who has been jailed without bail for nearly five years,
was granted $3 million bail just before Christmas. In spite of
pledges of property, he has been unable to raise the necessary
$300,000 in cash to gain release.
   But Davis says his client is in ``pretty good spirits,''
sustained by the knowledge he will one day get to tell his side
from the witness stand.
   Perhaps the most powerful figure in the courtroom is Superior
Court Judge William Pounders, who tries every day to move things
along quickly.
   Last November, one year after he took over the McMartin case,
Pounders marked the date by declaring, ``I don't intend to see
another anniversary date. I intend to conclude the case within the
next year.''
</TEXT>
