<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Dale     02-28 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Dale,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Fire In Theater Leads To Big Laughs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a small fire broke out above the stage of
the Marquis Theater, ``Me and My Girl'' star Jim Dale kept cool, as
did the full house of 1,600.
   Nobody was hurt in the incident, which interrupted Saturday's
matinee about 15 minutes into the first act of the
Tony-award-winning musical and sparked Dale's sense of humor.
   ``You've got to expect this if you come to see the hottest show
on Broadway,'' Dale told the playgoers after they filed back into
the theater after a 40-minute interruption.
   An overheated cable ignited a piece of rope in the proscenium
arch, out of view of the audience, said stage manager John Bonanni.
   ``There was a smell of smoke during the first scene, and after I
made my exit, I said, `Something's burning,''' Dale recalled Sunday.
   ``Then I heard a commotion, and I thought, `That's not in the
scene, shouting and carrying on.' I looked out, and people were
rushing out, up the aisles.''
   One of the show's managers calmed the crowd, which filed out in
an orderly fashion, Bonanni said. The fire was quickly extinguished
by stagehands.
   After city firefighters made a safety check, the audience was
let back in.
   A few jokes ``got them in a damn good mood,'' and then Dale
recapped the play's action up to the point of the fire and
retreated backstage.
   Dale, who plays a Cockney commoner who lands in the lap of
English aristocracy, said he ``couldn't resist an ad lib'' in a
later scene.
   ``I say to the butler, `You haven't got a cigarette, have you,
mate?' Then I turned to the audience and said, `I promise I won't
light up,''' he said.
   He thinks the incident cast a warm glow over the audience _
figuratively speaking.
   ``They love to be involved in something fresh and new,'' he
said. ``We can't supply a fire every day, though.''
</TEXT>
