<2ND_LINE>AM-Calif Earthquakes,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swarm Of Quakes Jiggles Border Area, No Damage Or Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL CENTRO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A swarm of earthquakes shook the desert
on both sides of the California-Mexico border but no damage or
injuries were reported from the late-night tremors, authorities
said Sunday.
   Six quakes measuring between 3.0 and 4.1 on the Richter scale
struck between 9 p.m. Saturday and midnight, clustered 19 miles
southwest of El Centro in the Imperial Valley and 75 miles east of
San Diego, said spokesman Robert Finn at the California Institute
of Technology in Pasadena.
   The last three tremors were felt in Mexicali, a Mexican border
town that was shaken by damaging quakes on Nov. 23 and 24, said
fire department Lt. Antonio Makallon.
   ``Many panicked and fearful people called, but only those who
were in their houses felt the tremors,'' he said in Spanish.
   The November quakes caused four deaths, at least 94 minor
injuries and millions of dollars in damage on both sides of the
border. Those quakes registered 6.2 and 6.6 on the Richter scale.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable
damage, 6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
