<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Light Snow In Upper Midwest, Rain In Southern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation enjoyed sunny skies Sunday, with temperatures
seasonably cool in the Northeast and seasonably mild in many other
sections.
   Light snow fell in scattered sections of Wisconsin and upper
Michigan and rain dampened the southern coast of California and
parts of Nevada. A few patches of dense fog remained along the
Texas Gulf Coast.
   About one-third of an inch of rain fell at Lovelock, Nev., and
Los Angeles during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST. An inch of
snow fell at Houghton, Mich., during the same period.
   At noon, temperatures were in the 30s in much of New England,
the 30s and 40s from the Great Lakes through the upper Missouri
Valley, and the 40s and 50s in the Pacific Northwest. Across the
South, noontime temperatures were in the 60s and 70s across
Florida, the 70s and low 80s in much of Texas and the 60s and 70s
across the desert Southwest and Southern California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 25 at
Jackson, Wyo., and Limestone, Maine, to 84 at Cotulla, Texas. The
low for the nation Sunday morning was 7 below zero at Houlton,
Maine.
   For Monday, snow showers were predicted in the lower Great
Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and upper Michigan, while rain showers
were expected to fall in much of California and be widely scattered
in Idaho and Utah.
   Highs will be in the teens and 20s in northern Maine, upper
Michigan, Wisconsin and much of Minnesota; the 30s and 40s from
southern Maine across Maryland, the remainder of the Great Lakes,
the Ohio Valley, the central Mississippi Valley, the northern half
of the Plains and the northern Rockies; the 70s from southern
Georgia and Florida across the lower Mississippi Valley; and in the
70s and 80s in Texas and the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, the highs
will generally reach the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
