<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0780,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Head Toward New Round of `War of the Cities'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Iraqi report of air raids
on two Iranian cities. Pickup 4th pvs: Tehran's War ... Deletes
last four grafs which moved up and edits to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian warplanes, usually crippled by
shortages of spare parts, bombed three key economic targets in Iraq
on Sunday. Iraq retaliated with air raids on two Iranian cities.
   Baghdad's state radio said Iraqi jets bombed the cities of
Hamadan in eastern Iran and Dezful in the southeast in simultaneous
raids at 9 p.m.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said the attacks were in
retaliation for ``recent atrocities and crimes committed by the
charlatans of Iran.''
   Iran did not immediately confirm the Iraqi raids.
   In a separate dispatch, the Iraqi News Agency said Iranian
artillery over the weekend shelled ``purely civilian targets'' in
six Iraqi border towns and cities. It said said several people were
killed or wounded but gave no casualty figures.
   An earlier communique said two women and a child were killed and
several people, including four women, were wounded in Sunday's
shelling. It said seven civilians were killed and 16 wounded in
Basra and al-Qurna on Saturday.
   Tehran's War Information Headquarters said in a statement that
Iranian warplanes bombed a petrochemical plant in the southern port
of Basra, oil installations in Abul Khassib and a bridge linking
Umm Rassas island, in the disputed Shatt al-Arab waterway, with
mainland Iraq.
   The tiny island is a forward Iraqi position southeast of Basra
on the southern sector of the front with Iran.
   All Iranian planes returned safely to base from the
``successful'' midmorning raids, said the communique, broadcast by
Tehran Radio and monitored in Nicosia.
   An exchange of air raids that began Saturday have prompted fears
that a new round of the ``war of the cities'' is beginning.
   Thousands of civilians have been killed in Iraq and Iran during
such attacks. Hostilities on population centers generally are
preceded by accusations and warnings similar to those Tehran and
Baghdad exchanged this weekend.
   The Iranian air force was out of action for most of 1987. In
January, Iranian warplanes resumed combat missions against Iraq, an
indication that Tehran had somehow acquired spare parts for its
U.S.-built jets.
   Western military analysts say Iran has about 70 operational
combat aircraft, including F-4 and F-5 fighter-bombers and F-14
interceptors.
   Iraq, with more than 500 Soviet and French warplanes, has
maintained air supremacy in the 7-year-old gulf war.
   The Iranian war communique said the raids Sunday were in
retaliation for Iraqi strikes the day before on civilian targets in
a Tehran suburb and in the town of Saghez, in the northwestern
Azerbaijan Province.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency reported 25 civilians killed
and an unspecified number wounded in the Iraqi raids Saturday.
   The Iraqi News Agency denied Iraq hit any civilians targets over
the weekend.
   Iraqi air force commander Air Marshal Hamid Shaaban also warned
the Iranians against carrying out their threats.
   ``It is an illusion that Iran believes Iraq will succumb to
threats of attacking the cities,'' Shaaban said in an interview
with Baghdad's official Ath-Thawra newspaper.
   Shaaban said Iraq had drawn plans to ``strike at strategic
Iranian targets and also at the nests, where the rotten heads are
being sheltered.''
   That was a reference to headquarters of Iranian leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
