<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietMeiman     02-28 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Meiman,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Activists Arrive In Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old Soviet Jew who battled for
13 years to leave the Soviet Union embraced his daughter when he
arrived Sunday in Israel.
   ``Some of us managed to get out _ many are still left behind,''
said mathematician Naum Meiman, referring to Soviet emigration
policies.
   Meiman arrived in Israel the same day as another leading Soviet
Jewish activist, electrical engineer Lev Shapiro, who came here
with his wife and two children.
   Meiman hugged his daughter, Olga Plam, 50, of Boulder, Colo.,
after she arrived at Ben Gurion Airport aboard a flight from the
United States. She left the Soviet Union 14 years ago and had not
seen her father since then.
   Soviet authorities said they delayed Meiman's emigration request
because of his ``access to state secrets.'' Meiman had worked in
classified mathematical calculations in 1955.
   Meiman linked his release to the policy of glasnost _ greater
political openness on some topics _ initiated by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``It is true that it's easier to breathe in the Soviet Union
nowadays, after glasnost,'' he said. ``However, in essence nothing
has changed.''
   The Soviet Union allowed 8,011 Jews to emigrate in 1987, up from
less than a thousand annually in recent years but still far short
of the more than 50,000 permitted to leave in 1979.
   Meiman was met by representatives of the Weizman Institute of
Science and Tel Aviv University. Both institutions have offered the
scientist opportunities to continue his work in Israel, where
Meiman plans to settle.
   Meiman left Moscow Friday and rested in Vienna Saturday. His
wife, Inna Kitrosskaya, struggled for years for an exit visa for
cancer treatment in the United States. She received permission and
left the Soviet Union last year, but died 15 days later of a stroke.
   Meiman was not allowed to accompany his wife or to attend her
funeral.
   Shapiro, of Leningrad, was accompanied by his wife Leah, 38, his
son Yisrael, 13, and the 9-year-old daughter Naomi.
   The Shapiro family, which had been refused emigration permits
for 11 years, gained international prominence when Naomi wrote a
letter to Gorbachev, saying:
   ``You are known as a kind and good grandfather. Why don't you
let me meet my grandparents who live in Israel?''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain and U.S. and French
authorities also intervened on behalf of the Shapiros.
</TEXT>
