<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Art     02-28 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Art,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate Against Art Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 100,000 people demonstrated
peacefully Sunday to protest an art exhibition in which a print of
Marilyn Monroe's face was imposed on a picture of the Virgin of
Guadalupe, Mexico's patron saint.
   The demonstration was organized by four Roman Catholic religious
organizations and the people gathered in the capital's main Zocalo
Square. They then marched five miles to the Basilica at La Villa,
where an image of the Virgin of Guadalupe is enshrined.
   Many marchers carried signs denouncing the Museum of Modern Art
exhibition. The museum is run by the Institute of Fine Arts, an
agency of the Department of Education.
   On Jan. 23, about 1,000 people chanting ``Long live Christ the
king!'' stormed the museum in the city's central Chapultepec Park
and authorities closed the exhibit by painter Rolando de la Rosa.
   The museum director, Jorge Alberto Manrique, resigned last
Thursday at the government's request. Manrique had criticized the
closing of the exhibition.
   More than 100 Mexican artists and intellectuals expressed in a
statement their ``profound indignation'' and called for Manrique's
reinstatement.
   More than 90 percent of Mexico's 80 million people are Catholics.
   In one work, de la Rosa, 36, superimposed the face of the late
actress Marilyn Monroe on an image of the Virgin of Guadalupe.
   In another, styled after Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper,''
Jesus Christ had the face of the late Mexican actor and singer
Pedro Infante. In ``The Sacred Family,'' the baby Jesus was
replaced by a soccer ball.
</TEXT>
