<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Wales,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welsh Nationalists Make Incendiary Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Welsh nationalist group claimed
responsibility Sunday for four incendiary attacks on offices of
real estate firms that have been selling vacation homes in Wales to
English people.
   Four offices in the English city of Chester near the Welsh
border were damaged in the Saturday night attacks.
   Police said the incendiary devices were placed through the
letterboxes of the buildings.
   A group calling itself Meibion Glyndwr (Sons of Glendower, in
the Welsh language), asserted responsibility in a telephone call to
a journalist, saying speculators and ``collaborators'' must get out
of Wales.
   Named after the 15th century Welshman Owen Glendower who failed
in a bid to win independence from the English, the organization has
previously claimed responsibility for starting fires at
English-owned vacation cottages in Wales.
   No arrests have been made.
   Dafydd Thomas, president of the Welsh nationalist political
party Plaid Cymru and a member of the British Parliament, condemned
the attacks and urged Welsh people to give any information about
extremists to police.
