<HEAD>British Jet, Bound For U.S., Returns To Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inserts new 2d graf two runways closed briefly. Pickup 2nd pvs:
`The Boeing ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Airways jumbo jet carrying 281
passengers to the United States Sunday returned to Britain and made
an emergency landing because its wing slats malfunctioned, an
airline spokesman said.
   A piece of a wing flap fell from the jet as it landed at
Heathrow airport and two runways were closed temporarily for
inspection but no debris was found, according to Press Association,
the British domestic news agency.
   The Boeing 747 took off just after noon. Shortly into the flight
the pilot found he could not retract the slats on one wing, said
the spokesman.
   Wing slats project at an angle at the edge of each wing. By
increasing the area of the wing, the slats increase a plane's lift.
   The airline spokesman said the pilot dumped the aircraft's fuel
and returned to London about an hour later.
   ``The wing slats would not go back in but the problem would not
have caused any serious control difficulties,'' he said.
   ``The pilot decided to return as a precaution and because he did
not want to fly the Atlantic with a fault on the aircraft. There
was no danger and the aircraft made a perfectly normal landing.''
   British Airways said the passengers would either be flown to the
United States on another one of its aircraft or rebooked on another
airline.
   The plane had been heading to Washington, D.C., and Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
