<HEAD>Bush To Skip League Of Women Voters Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Republican Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush is planning to skip
the League of Women Voters' debate next week in Nashville, his
campaign manager said Sunday, in what one opposing camp called a
``front-runner's strategy.''
   ``At this time, there are no debates on the schedule,'' Lee
Atwater told reporters after a debate Sunday in Atlanta. ``We're
simply at a point where we've got 20 states; you've got to maintain
control of your schedule.''
   Bush was the last Republican candidate to agree to participate
the League's first debate in New Hampshire two weeks ago. He had
not publicly committed to attending the League's debate in
Nashville next Sunday.
   Atwater said Bush had no plans to participate in future debates
but added ``Never say never.''
   The league has also scheduled two debates _ one for the
Republican candidates and one for the Democrats _ later in the
primary season.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole would like to debate Bush
one-on-one, his campaign said after the Atlanta debate on Sunday.
   ``We're looking for a one-on-one debate with the vice president,
'' said Dole campaign manager Bill Brock, ``but I think he's
following a front-runner's strategy.''
   Bush is far ahead in the polls on the primaries to be held on
March 8, dubbed Super Tuesday, when nearly a third of the delegates
to the GOP convention.
   The Democratic League debate is also scheduled next Sunday in
Nashville. The GOP debate was moved by the League from its original
Saturday date to Sunday to accomodate candidates' schedules.
   The South Carolina GOP primary will be held on Saturday.
