<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Strikes,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News, Air and Train Strikes in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travellers were frustrated Sunday by a new wave of
airport and railway personnel strikes while Italians had few
newspapers to read about their Olympic skiing hero Alberto Tomba.
   Alitalia, Italy's state-run airline, canceled hundreds of
flights to and from Rome's airports because of a 24-hour strike by
ground personnel. It was the latest in a series of walkouts to
protest lack of progress in contract renewal negotiations.
   Alitalia's intercontinental flights and its connections to
Italy's islands operated normally, as did flights by other
airlines. Passengers, however, often had to wait for more than hour
for their baggage.
   New contract talks are set to begin Monday.
   Long-distance train service from Rome's main station suffered
disruptions from a 24-hour strike by railway employees that started
at 9 p.m.
   Italy's major daily newspapers did not publish Sunday as a
result of a 48-hour nationwide walkout by journalists protesting
stalemated contract talks. Only a few regional papers exempt from
the strike came out Sunday.
   Television and radio ran limited news broadcasts Sunday without
film reports. On Monday, television and radio stations are to
cancel all newscasts.
   The journalists' strike prevented most Italians from reading
about the exploits of Tomba, who won his second Olympic gold medal
Saturday in alpine skiing.
   Paese Sera, one of the dailies exempt from the strike, ran a
front-page headline saying ``Alberto Tomba Is Already a Legend.''
</TEXT>
