<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Senators-BankProbe     02-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senators-Bank Probe,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Senators Who Accepted Contributions From Company Met With
Regulators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five U.S. senators who accepted a total of
$297,000 in contributions from an Arizona company and its employees
met with federal bank examiners investigating one of its
subsidiaries, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   Within three months of the meeting, examiners backed off and
ultimately cleared the subsidiary, Lincoln Savings and Loan
Association of Irvine, Calif., of wrongdoing, The Detroit News
quoted unidentified sources as saying.
   The thrift is owned by Phoenix, Ariz.-based American Continental
Corp. Executives of the company and its subsidiaries made the
donations over the past several years, the newspaper reported.
   Those accepting the contributions and the amounts, according to
the News, were: Alan Cranston, D-Calif., $41,900; Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz., $43,000; John Glenn, D-Ohio, $34,000; John McCain,
R-Ariz., $112,000; and Don Riegle, D-Mich., $66,100.
   Riegle said there was no connection between the contribution
toward his 1988 re-election campaign and the April 9, 1987, meeting
in which he and the four other senators discussed the investigation
with Federal Home Loan Bank Board examiners.
   ``If there was the slightest suggestion or hint that somehow
somebody was going to contribute in return for some kind of
favorable consideration, we don't want that money,'' Riegle said.
``I wouldn't accept it.''
   Aides to the other senators said none was available to comment
late last week, the newspaper reported.
   The banking investigators were looking into high-risk
investments made by Lincoln that could threaten its solvency, the
News said.
   The contributions were permissible under federal election laws.
Riegle's campaign chairman, Kevin Gottlieb, said the timing of the
donations and the meeting with regulators was ``an interesting
coincidence.''
   Riegle told the newspaper he attended the meeting because he is
a senior member of the Senate Banking Committee and wanted to
ensure Lincoln Savings received a fair review.
   He said he was invited to the meeting by the other senators and
was concerned Lincoln was being harassed.
   The newspaper quoted an unidentified source as saying that after
the meeting, the probe changed direction.
   San Francisco bank examiners ``were ready to ask for an
enforcement action against Lincoln,'' an unidentified California
bankig official was quoted as saying. ``But that has changed. The
scope of the examination has changed.''
   American Continental spokesman Andy Baer characterized the
events differently.
   ``I wouldn't say (the examiners) backed off; I would say there
is a new spirit of cooperation,'' Baer said.
   The final bank examiner's report recommended no sanctions
against Lincoln, said Robert Kielty, American Continental's
corporate counsel.
</TEXT>
