<HEAD>Midway Jet Makes Unscheduled Landing; Pilot Reports Some Smoke In
Cockpit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf with 3 grafs to add comment from airline
spokeswoman, flight resuming. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Midway Airlines 737 flying from Tampa
to Chicago made an unscheduled landing here Sunday after its pilot
reported an electrical problem that produced smoke in the cockpit,
authorities said.
   Flight 793, with 119 passengers and five crew members aboard,
landed safely at Gainesville Regional Airport about 1:20 p.m. with
no injuries reported, said Federal Aviation Administration shift
supervisor V.H. Steed.
   ``It was a precautionary measure,'' he said. ``None of the
passengers were ever in danger.''
   Gainesville Fire Department spokesman Stew Schwartz said the
pilot asked that fire crews be ready because of an unusual odor and
some smoke in the cockpit.
   Midway spokeswoman Sandra Allen in Chicago said smoke apparently
came from an electrical problem.
   ``At this point, we don't know exactly what caused the smoke,''
she said. ``Two of our mechanics from Miami are being sent to
Gainesville to inspect the plane.''
   The passengers waited in the airport's terminal for about two
hours until another Midway plane was flown in and the flight
resumed, Ms. Allen said. The Boeing jet will remain in Gainesville
until the mechanics declare it fit to fly, she said.
