<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT director's name to D.W. Griffith.
Members who used a0684, AM-Obit-Oslund, sent Feb. 27 under a
Honolulu dateline, or a0697, AM-Deaths, sent the same day, are
asked to use the following story.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press incorrectly reported Sunday
that Lula E. ``Tiny'' Oslund, 91, who died here Thursday, was
silent screen star Blanche Sweet.
   Ms. Sweet, who worked with filmmaker D.W. Griffith, died Sept.
6, 1986, in New York.
   Mrs. Oslund's son, Wilman F. Oslund, said Sunday that he had
honored a request from his mother that her obituary identify her as
Ms. Sweet. ``In her mind, she was Blanche Sweet,'' said Oslund, 55.
   Oslund said his mother had always told him she was the silent
screen star who played heroines for Griffith in such films as ``The
Lonedale Operator'' (1911) and ``Judith of Bethulia'' (1913).
   Oslund said he saw no harm in complying with his mother's
request. He said that he believes his mother worked as a stand-in
for Ms. Sweet and that Mrs. Oslund closely resembled the actress.
   Author Joseph F. Clarke identified Ms. Sweet as Daphne Wayne in
his 1977 book ``Pseudonyms: The Names Behind the Names.''
