<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Albania-Tour,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Group Of Yugoslav Tourists In Albania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albania has allowed its first group
of Yugoslav tourists into the secluded and closely guarded Eastern
European nation, Yugoslavia's official Tanjug news agency reported
Sunday.
   The weekend trip by 130 tourists, organized by a Slovenian
travel company and Albantours, included visits to the Albanian
capital of Tirana as well as Durres, Elbasan and Shkoder.
   The communist nation of 2.8 million has permitted very limited
tourism and trips by a few foreign journalists since the late
1940s, but the nation's attendance of a meeting of Balkan foreign
ministers in Belgrade last week was seen as the latest sign of
Albania's slow abandonment of isolation.
   At last week's meeting, Foreign Minister Reis Malile of Albania
became the first Albanian government minister to visit neighboring
Yugoslavia since World War II.
</TEXT>
