<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Democrats-Debate     02-28 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Debate,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats _ Minus Gephardt and Dukakis _ Debate In Houston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential candidates debated
the problems of the South on Sunday _ minus front-runners Michael
Dukakis and Richard Gephardt.
   It was the Democrats' second debate in two days, with one more
talkfest on the schedule Monday.
   ``Apparently, they don't care much about Texas and the South,''
former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart said of the missing contenders.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. also criticized the two absent
candidates at the first opportunity.
   ``Maybe they didn't enjoy the debate last week in Dallas,'' Gore
said. ``We miss them and I want them to know they're missed,'' he
added.
   Simon, who announced last week he would not campaign actively in
the Super Tuesday states, said his presence Sunday proved he was
not writing off the South.
   ``I need and want and care for your votes,'' he said after the
debate. He said there were no winners or losers in the debate
``with the exception'' of Dukakis and Gephardt.
   The Massachusetts governor and the Missouri congressman have
been trading victories in the early contests. Gephardt won Iowa;
Dukakis won New Hampshire. Gephardt won South Dakota; Dukakis won
Minnesota. On Sunday, Dukakis won Maine's Democratic caucuses.
   Jackson was the only candidate who did not criticize Gephardt
and Dukakis for not coming to Houston.
   ``I do not know why they chose not to be here. I do not think it
reflects a lack of interest or lack of integrity. They simply made
other priorities,'' he said.
   Debate spokeswoman Dee Shoup said Gephardt and Dukakis cited
scheduling conflicts.
   About 800 people attended the debate at the George R. Brown
Convention Center, and the forum was televised.
   Former CBS anchorman Walter Cronkite hosted the debate, but he
did not question the candidates. Television journalist Linda
Ellerbee was the moderator.
   Several of the candidates described themselves as providing
leadership to the rest of the field.
   ``My presence has influenced the other leaders,'' Jackson said.
``You now hear Gephardt saying we must challenge the multinational
corporations _ that's Jesse Jackson. When you now hear Congress
saying stop the drug flow _ that's Jesse Jackson. When you hear
other candidates talking about South Africa for the first time _
that's Jesse Jackson.''
   Hart, too, said he was showing the way for the rest.
   ``I'm the only one who has put out a budget, although I see each
of these people gradually creeping towards that inevitability that
I think they are going to have to face.
   ``The fundamental point here is that Paul talks about his
programs, Jesse talks about his programs, and Al talks about his.
I'm the only one who puts out a budget to tell Americans the
truth,'' he said.
   On another subject, Gore said he supports a national energy
policy that includes a price floor, incentives for domestic oil
production and discouragement of oil imports.
   ``We have got to have a national energy policy,'' he said.
   The candidates appeared before the National Association of
Television Program Executives.
</TEXT>
