<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Fighting     02-28 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Fighting,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Victory In Angolan Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels claimed they
killed 172 government soldiers and captured three Soviet-built
tanks in recent fighting, the independent South African Press
Association reported Sunday.
   The guerrillas destroyed three Angolan military units Friday in
a battle east of Cuito Cuanavale in southeastern Angola, the news
agency reported. It cited a statement released at rebel
headquarters in Jamba.
   UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
also claimed its guerrillas killed 10 Cuban soldiers and destroyed
seven Soviet-made T-55 tanks, the report said.
   The statement said five rebels were killed and four were wounded
in Friday's battles.
   Both Angola's Marxist government and the U.S.-  and South
African-supported rebels have reported heavy fighting around Cuito
Cuanavale in recent weeks.
   UNITA said in January that it forced government troops to flee
Cuito Cuanavale and guerrilla forces encircled the vacated town.
UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi has been predicting his rebels would
defeat the remaining government in the area and then move into
Cuito Cuanavale.
   The town was used as a government base in annual dry-season
offensives against UNITA strongholds in the southeast.
   Angola gained its independence from Portugal in Novermber 1975,
and UNITA lost to the Marxist forces in the civil war that
followed. Government forces are backed by some 40,000 Cuban troops
and more than 1,000 Soviet military advisers.
   Also Sunday, South Africa announced that two of its soldiers
were killed in Angola. The military statement said the troops were
slain Thursday by ``indirect enemy fire.''
   South Africa announced in November that it had intervened
militarily in southern Angola on behalf of UNITA. A month later
South Africa said it had begun to withdraw its troops, but it
remains engaged in the fighting.
   South Africa has announced the deaths of more than 30 South
African military personnel since November, but has not disclosed
the extent of its involvement. Angola claims 9,000 South African
troopers are in Angola.
</TEXT>
