<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TaiwanDissident     02-28 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan Dissident,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Dissident Agrees To Voluntary Deportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese dissident arrested trying
to board a flight to Taiwan with a false passport said Monday he
agreed to leave the Philippines and would depart for the United
States.
   Hsu Hsin-Liang said he would leave Monday aboard a Korean Air
flight for Seoul, South Korea, and would travel on to Hawaii.
   Hsu, who edits The Taiwan Times newspaper in Los Angeles, was
banned from Taiwan in 1979 for political activity.
   Immigration officials said Hsu agreed to self-deportation,
meaning he would be free to return to the Philippines. Philippine
authorities had offered to accept him as a political refugee but he
declined, saying he wanted to return to Taiwan.
   Hsu was arrested Feb. 11 while preparing to board a flight for
the Taiwanese capital of Taipei.
   Taiwanese officials refused to allow him to return to Taiwan
because people charged with sedition are not allowed to enter the
country under the National Security Law, which replaced martial
rule last July.
   Taiwan had been under martial law since 1949, when the
Nationalist Chinese lost a mainland civil war with the Communists,
fled to the island and established a government.
   Hsu was charged with sedition for his alleged involvement in an
anti-government riot in Taiwan's southern port of Kaohsiung in
1979. The riot occurred two months after Hsu had left for the
United States, but Taiwanese officials said he helped organize it.
   In September 1986, Hsu organized a U.S.-based Taiwanese group,
the Democratic Progressive Party Overseas that is affiliated with
Taiwan's opposition Democratic Progressive Party.
</TEXT>
