<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ireland     02-28 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body of Man Slain at Army Checkpoint Exhumed for Autopsy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONAGHAN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a 23-year-old Northern
Ireland man fatally shot at a British army checkpoint was exhumed
Sunday for another autopsy in Ireland.
   Aidan McAnespie's family requested the new autopsy. They said he
had been harassed at the border and disputed the army statement
that the bullet that struck him while he was near the border
checkpoint at Aughnacloy, in Northren Ireland, on Feb. 21 was fired
accidentally and ricocheted.
   An 18-year-old soldier has been charged with unlawful killing in
the death and is being held on bail in military care.
   The British and Irish governments are conducting separate
investigations.
   McAnespie's body was buried Tuesday in Clara, County Monaghan,
in the Irish Republic across the border from Aughnacloy following
an autopsy by British medical examiners.
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey of Ireland on Saturday approved
the exhumation after receiving a request from the family.
   An overnight police guard was placed at the cordoned-off grave,
and after the exhumation the coffin was transferred to Monaghan
General Hospital for the autopsy.
   The dead man's sister, Eilish McCabe, claimed Sunday that her
brother had received a number of death threats from British
soldiers.
   She said in an an Irish radio interview that her brother
received ``continuous harassment'' during border crossings from his
Northern Ireland home to his job in the Irish Republic.
   Haughey is to make a statement on the incident to the Dail,
Ireland's parliament, Tuesday.
   Northern Ireland is a British province. Guerrillas of the mainly
Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army have been fighting since 1969
to unite the province, where Protestants outnumber Catholics 3-2,
with the predominantly Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
