<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VolckerComeback Bjt   02-28 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Volcker Comeback, Bjt,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcker Ends Self-Imposed Silence _ But Who Is Listening?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Does anyone pay attention to a 6-foot-7
kibbitzer who used to be the second most powerful man in Washington?
   Paul Volcker is beginning to find out.
   The former chairman of the Federal Reserve recently broke a
self-imposed vow of silence to resume offering opinions on
deficits, taxes and the health of the economy.
   He seemed to show a little of the old magical influence last
Thursday when stock and bond prices sank soon after he called for a
tax increase and predicted that interest rates would rise.
   But some skeptics said the markets' behavior had nothing to do
with what Volcker said.
   ``He's not even associated with the Fed anymore,'' said
Hildegarde Zagorski, a market strategist at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``When you get a day like (Thursday), everybody tries to say
what killed the market and they drag out every news item that would
have passed unnoticed,'' she said.
   So is Volcker capable of moving the market? ``No. Not at all,''
Ms. Zagorski said.
   Volcker still has not settled down to a new job since his
departure from the Federal Reserve last August, when he was
succeeded by Alan Greenspan. But Volcker is expected to announce
his career decision within the next few weeks.
   Meanwhile, he is borrowing an office on Wall Street and heading
a Washington-based commission on how to improve the quality of the
nation's civil service.
   Speaking on the lecture circuit helps pay the bills and gives
Volcker a forum to express his views on the need to cut the federal
budget deficit.
   The forum for his remarks Thursday was a luncheon meeting in San
Antonio of the National Association of Industrial and Office Parks.
   The night before, Volcker had spoken in Peoria, Ill., at the
Washington Day banquet of the Creve Coeur Club.
   In Peoria, Volcker was chosen as a contrast to the 1987 speaker,
Bob Hope.
   ``We certainly know it's difficult to upstage a Bob Hope, so we
said let's go back to something that's not comparable,'' said Henry
Allovio, the club's vice president.
   According to those who believe in Volcker's continuing
influence, his remarks in San Antonio triggered a selloff in the
bond market, which scared owners of stock-index futures, which in
turn dragged down stock prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had been up as
much as 33 points, ended up with a loss for the day of 22.38
points, most of it in the final hour of trading.
   ``I have deep respect for Paul Volcker and in my opinion there
is not a single more influential economist in this country,'' said
John V. Sebastian, executive vice president and chief economist of
Clayton Brown & Associates in Chicago.
   But can Volcker influence trading decisions even without the
control over the nation's money supply that he once had? Yes,
Sebastian said.
   As an example, he mentioned Henry Kaufman, a prominent economist
for the giant Wall Street investment firm Salomon Brothers Inc.
whose outlooks used to move interest rates in the bond market. In
December Kaufman announced plans to start his own consulting firm.
   ``Henry Kaufman in his heyday had no authority and yet he was
able to influence the markets,'' Sebastian said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
