<1ST_LINE>d f AM-Autos-Engineers     02-28 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Autos-Engineers,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Engineers Gather in Detroit Monday Through Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 automotive engineers will meet
this week to talk about everything concerning the life of a
vehicle, from computerized conception to disposal on the junk heap.
   The Society for Automotive Engineers 1988 Congress and
Exposition also will be attended by more than 700 industry
suppliers, who will display their latest developments in automotive
plastics and other materials, lubricants, design systems and
maintenance. They'll occupty 167,000 square feet of exhibit space
at Detroit's downtown Cobo Hall from Monday through Thursday.
   The convention's theme is ``Engineering for the '90s _
Imagination, Innovation.'' Among featured speakers will be General
Motors Corp. President Robert Stempel and Anthony Rudd, deputy
chairman of Lotus Engineering.
   Special sessions include a panel's look at the growing problem
of disposing of automotive plastics as their use expands
internally, in the engine and passenger compartment, and
externally, as more and more body parts are composed of stronger,
reinforced plastic substances.
   The engineers also will discuss efforts to reduce release of
ozone-depleting chloroflourocarbons, or CFCs, used in production.
Automaking has been the main source of CFC emissions since the
United States ended CFC use in aerosol sprays in the 1970s.
   Ford Motor Co. Vice Chairman Harold Poling will be honored
Monday at a luncheon hosted by Automotive Industries magazine,
which named him its Man of the Year for 1988. The trade magazine
noted Poling's stabilizing, corporate-wide strategy of cost-cutting
and balanced production while focusing on quality and cooperation
with workers, dealers and suppliers.
   The strategy has allowed Ford to run factories at profitable
levels, introduce attractive innovations and eliminate most plant
closures, the magazine reported in a cover story on Poling.
   As a result, Ford outearned GM, the much larger industry leader,
in 1986 and 1987 and is expected to remain the biggest money-maker
in the industry in 1988, while GM is still fighting to cut costs
and balance a huge modernization and new products program.
   Described as the largest vehicle engineering conference, the
gathering will include engineers from Ford, GM, Chrysler Corp.,
Toyota Motor Corp., Honda Motor Co. as well as hundreds of
suppliers including Allied Automotive, Borg-Warner, DuPont
Automotive, General Electric, United Technologies and Dow Chemical.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880228-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-88 2008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankBid     02-28 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Bank, Target of Hostile Takeover, Predicts Bitter Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp., target of a $1.08 billion
hostile takeover proposal by Bank of New York that was sanctioned
last week by government regulators, said Sunday it would brief
shareholders on why they should reject the bid and predicted a
bitterly fought battle for their votes.
   ``Irving plans to bring to the attention of its shareholders all
the factors they should consider regarding the offer, as well as
questioning exactly how Bank of New York intends to meet the
numerous conditions to which its offer is now subject,'' the bank
said in a press statement.
   It was Irving's first official reaction to the approval given
last Thursday by the Federal Reserve Board and New York State
Banking Board Bank of the Bank of New York's hostile $60 a share
bid in cash and securities.
   The takeover fight has attracted attention because hostile
acquisitions are unusual in the normally staid banking world. Some
analysts have said government approval portends hostile takeovers
of other banks.
   Fed and state officials dismissed the unfriendly nature of the
bid as irrelevant and said they saw no competitive threat to a
merger of the two New York Banks, which would create the nation's
12th largest banking company with assets of nearly $42 billion.
   Nevertheless, the Fed imposed one important condition of
approval by requiring Bank of New York to sell additional stock to
replenish the $264 million cash portion of the takeover. In
addition, the Fed said at least 60 percent of that amount must be
raised before the transaction can be completed.
   Although Bank of New York officials expressed confidence they
could meet the condition, Irving called it significant hurdles
because it will dilute the stock's value and must be approved by
Bank of New York shareholders.
   The Bank of New York's offer depends on receipt of two-thirds of
Irving's shares. The offer could encounter more difficulty because
of a New York law that impedes hostile takeovers.
   Irving said the Fed's approval ``clearly opens the way for a
bitterly fought proxy battle.''
   Proxies are written statements authorizing others to vote stock
on the behalf of shareholders, a normal arrangement in publicly
held companies. Management routinely solicits shareholder proxies
but they are also used by others attempting to win control away
from management.
   ``The Fed's approval does not change the nature of the proposal,
which continues to make no business sense and is not in the best
long-term interest of Irving,'' said the Irving statement.
   It said the bank ``is fully committed to continue opposing this
grossly inadequate and highly conditional proposal, which the
corporation's unanimous board is convinced is not in Irving's best
interests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
